\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States national amateur boxing heavyweight champions|U.S. heavyweight champion]]\n|years=2007}}\n{{s-after|after=Jeremiah Graziano}}\n{{s-before|before=Joseph Heysquierdo}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of US national Golden Gloves heavyweight champions|U.S. Golden Gloves<br>heavyweight champion]]\n|years=2007}}\n{{s-after|after=Preston Lewis}}\n{{s-text|style=background:#C1D8FF; font-weight: bold;|text=Regional boxing titles}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-vac|last=[[Chauncy Welliver]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[World Boxing Council|WBC]] Continental Americas<br>heavyweight champion\n|years=December 15, 2012 \u2013 January 17, 2015<br>Won world title}}\n{{s-vac|next=[[Tony Thompson (boxer)|Tony Thompson]]}}\n{{s-text|style=background:#C1D8FF; font-weight: bold;|text=World boxing titles}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bermane Stiverne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of WBC world champions#Heavyweight|WBC heavyweight champion]]\n|years=January 17, 2015 \u2013 February 22, 2020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tyson Fury]]}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-before|before=Gabriel Bracero<br>{{small|KO1 [[Danny O'Connor (boxer)|Danny O'Connor]]}} }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Premier Boxing Champions#Knockout of the Year|''PBC'' Knockout of the Year]]<br>{{small|KO9 [[Artur Szpilka]]}}\n|years=2016}}\n{{s-after|after=Deontay Wilder<br>{{small|KO1 Bermane Stiverne}} }}\n{{s-before|before=Deontay Wilder<br>{{small|KO9 Artur Szpilka}} }}\n{{s-ttl|title=''PBC'' Knockout of the Year<br>{{small|KO1 Bermane Stiverne}}\n|years=2017}}\n{{s-after|after=[[Naoya Inoue]]<br>{{small|KO1 [[Juan Carlos Payano]]}} }}\n{{s-before|before={{nowrap|[[James DeGale]] vs.}}<br>[[Badou Jack]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Premier Boxing Champions#Fight of the Year|''PBC'' Fight of the Year]]<br>{{small|[[Deontay Wilder vs. Luis Ortiz|vs. Luis Ortiz]]}}\n|years=2018}}\n{{s-non|reason={{abbr|TBA|To be announced}} }}\n{{s-before|before={{nowrap|[[Dominic Breazeale]] vs.}}<br>[[Izu Ugonoh]]<br>{{small|Round 3}} }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The Ring magazine Round of the Year#2010s|''The Ring'' Round of the Year]]<br>{{small|[[Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury|vs. Tyson Fury]]<br>Round 12}}\n|years=2018}}\n{{s-after|after={{nowrap|[[Anthony Joshua vs. Andy Ruiz Jr.|Andy Ruiz Jr. vs.<br>Anthony Joshua]]}}<br>{{small|Round 3}} }}\n{{s-before|before={{nowrap|[[John Molina Jr.]] vs.}}<br>[[Ivan Redkach]]<br>{{small|Round 3}} }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Premier Boxing Champions#Round of the Year|''PBC'' Round of the Year]]<br>vs. Tyson Fury<br>{{small|Round 12}}\n|years=2018}}\n{{s-non|reason=TBA}}\n{{s-before|before=Naoya Inoue<br>{{small|KO1 Juan Carlos Payano}} }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[The Ring magazine Knockout of the Year#2010s|''The Ring'' Knockout of the Year]]<br>{{small|[[Deontay Wilder vs. Luis Ortiz II|vs. Luis Ortiz II]]}}\n|years=2019}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilder, Deontay}}\n[[Category:African-American boxers]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n[[Category:National Golden Gloves champions]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Winners of the United States Championship for amateur boxers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for the United States in boxing]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Tuscaloosa, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Boxers from Alabama]]\n[[Category:World heavyweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:World Boxing Council champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Deontay Wilder\n| image = Deontay Wilder 2018.jpg{{!}}border\n| caption = Wilder in 2018\n| realname = Deontay Leshun Wilder\n| nickname = The Bronze Bomber\n| height = 6 ft 7 in<ref name=stats2018>''[[Showtime Championship Boxing]]'' tale of the tape prior to the [[Luis Ortiz (Cuban boxer)|Luis Ortiz]] fight.</ref>\n| reach = 83 in<ref name=stats2018/>\n| weight = [[Heavyweight]]\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|10|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama]], U.S.\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 44\n| wins = 42\n| KO = 41\n| losses = 1\n| draws = 1\n| no contests = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[amateur boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalOlympics}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing]] | [[Boxing at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Heavyweight|Heavyweight]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[United States national amateur boxing championships|U.S. National Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[List of United States national amateur boxing heavyweight champions|2007 Colorado Springs]]|Heavyweight}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Golden Gloves]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[List of US national Golden Gloves super heavyweight champions|2007 Chattanooga]] | Heavyweight}}\n}}\n\n'''Deontay Leshun Wilder''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|w|a\u026a|l|d|\u025c\u02d0r}}; born October 22, 1985) is an American [[professional boxer]]. He held the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[heavyweight]] title from 2015 to 2020, and in doing so became the first American world heavyweight champion in nine years, which was the longest period of time in boxing history without an American heavyweight champion. As of February 2020, he is ranked as the world's third-best active heavyweight by the [[Transnational Boxing Rankings Board]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tbrb.org/all-rankings/|title=RANKINGS {{!}} Transnational Boxing Rankings Board|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> fourth by ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'' magazine,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ringtv.com/ratings/|title=Ratings|last=|first=|date=|website=The Ring|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> and fifth by [[BoxRec]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/en/ratings?offset=0&sex=M&division=Heavyweight|title=BoxRec: Ratings|last=|first=|date=|website=boxrec.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWilder had a late start to boxing, taking up the sport at 20 years of age. As an [[amateur boxing|amateur]], he won a bronze medal in the heavyweight division at the [[2008 Olympics]]. This led to his nickname of \"The Bronze Bomber\", which Wilder coined after [[Joe Louis]], who was known by the nickname of \"The Brown Bomber\".\n\nWilder is particularly known for his formidable punching power, having knocked out every opponent he has faced, except [[Tyson Fury]].  His [[knockout]]-to-win ratio stands at 98%, with 20 knockouts in the first round. He is a two-time winner of the ''[[Premier Boxing Champions]]'' [[Premier Boxing Champions#Knockout of the Year|Knockout of the Year]] award, in 2016 and 2017, and the winner of the [[The Ring magazine Knockout of the Year|''Ring'' magazine Knockout of the Year]] award in 2019.\n\n==Amateur career==\nWilder started boxing in October 2005, when he entered Skyy Boxing Gym in [[Northport, Alabama]], and began training under Jay Deas. Wilder was 20 at that time.\n\nBy 2007, he upset the favorites to win both the [[National Golden Gloves]] and the [[National Amateur Heavyweight Champions|US championships]] at 201&nbsp;lb (91&nbsp;kg).\n\nAt the Golden Gloves, he defeated highly-touted cadet world champion [[Isiah Thomas (boxer)|Isiah Thomas]], a southpaw from Detroit, and David Thompson, of Brooklyn, in the finals. At the U.S. championship he defeated Quantis Graves and won the final 31\u201315 over southpaw James Zimmerman of San Jose, California.\n\nAt the Olympic trials, he beat Graves twice more and won the Olympic trials in only 21 bouts. Early in 2008 he scored a career-best win by edging out world championship silver medalist and future Olympic champion [[Rakhim Chakhkeiv|Rakhim Chakhiyev]] in Russia. He qualified for the Olympics by beating [[Deivi Julio Blanco|Deivis Julio]] 6:5 [[Jorge Qui\u00f1onez|Jorge Quinones]] from Ecuador on double countback and Brazilian [[Rafael Lima (boxer)|Rafael Lima]] 6:5 at the qualifier.\n\nIn a Russia-USA dual match on February 29, 2008, in [[Novosibirsk]], Wilder was knocked out by [[Evgenyi Romanov]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fr.sports.yahoo.com/news/boxe-evgeny-romanov-dernier-homme-084117921.html|title=Boxe: Evgeny Romanov, le dernier homme \u00e0 avoir mis KO le surpuissant Deontay Wilder|website=fr.sports.yahoo.com|language=fr-FR|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\nWilder then competed at heavyweight in the [[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Olympics]], defeating Abdelaziz Touilbini of Algeria and Mohamed Arjaoui of Morocco before losing to [[Clemente Russo]] of Italy in the semi-final to earn a bronze medal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.olympic.org/olympic-results/beijing-2008/boxing/81-91kg-heavyweight-m?event=31432|title=81 - 91kg (heavyweight) men results - Boxing - Beijing 2008 Olympics|website=www.olympic.org|access-date=2016-04-20}}</ref>\n\nWilder had an approximate amateur record of 30\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doghouseboxing.com/Gabriel/Montoya_110112.htm|title=Developing Deontay Wilder|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130114125605/http://doghouseboxing.com/Gabriel/Montoya_110112.htm|archive-date=2013-01-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Deontay_Wilder#Amateur_Highlights|title=Deontay Wilder - BoxRec|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118052830/http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Deontay_Wilder#Amateur_Highlights|archive-date=2017-01-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Olympic results===\n'''[[Boxing at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]''':<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://results.beijing2008.cn/WRM/ENG/Schedule/BX.shtml|title=Beijing results|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820170926/http://results.beijing2008.cn/WRM/ENG/Schedule/BX.shtml|archivedate=2008-08-20|df=}}</ref>\n*Defeated [[Abdelaziz Toulbini]] ([[Algeria]]) 10:4\n*Defeated [[Mohamed Arjaoui]] ([[Morocco]]) 10+:10 (tiebreaker criteria)\n*Lost to [[Clemente Russo]] ([[Italy]]) 1:7\n\n===World Championship results===\n'''[[2007 AIBA World Boxing Championships]]''':\n*Lost to [[Krzysztof Zimnoch]] ([[Poland]]) 20-23 (10/24/2007)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/WorldChamps2007.html|title=World Champs 2007|publisher=|access-date=2016-07-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416215928/http://amateur-boxing.strefa.pl/Championships/WorldChamps2007.html|archive-date=2016-04-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Early career===\nWilder made his professional debut at the age of 23 on November 15, 2008, at the Vanderbilt University Memorial Gymnasium in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]]. He faced Ethan Cox (2-2-1), winning by second-round [[technical knockout]] (TKO) after knocking Cox down three times. Wilder fought seven times in 2009, winning all the fights in round one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/sports/20090315/another-easy-win-for-wilder|title=Another easy win for Wilder|last=|first=|date=March 15, 2009|website=Tuscaloosa News|publisher=|access-date=January 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111005558/http://www.tuscaloosanews.com/sports/20090315/another-easy-win-for-wilder|archive-date=January 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> By October 2012, Wilder racked up a 25-fight win streak, winning all by knockout and all within four rounds. Some notable stoppages included former [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[heavyweight]] title challenger [[Owen Beck]] (27-10, 20 KOs), former [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] [[light heavyweight]] title challenger [[DeAndrey Abron]] (15-6, 10 KOs) and former WBO heavyweight challenger Damon Reed (46-15, 32 KOs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2012/06/deontay-wilder-destroys-owen-beck-in-3rd-round/|title=Deontay Wilder destroys Owen Beck in 3rd round!|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111000745/http://www.boxingnews24.com/2012/06/deontay-wilder-destroys-owen-beck-in-3rd-round/|archive-date=January 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-knocks-damon-reed-out-two-rounds--40528|title=Deontay Wilder Knocks Damon Reed Out in Two Rounds|last=|first=|date=June 19, 2011|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWilder won his first title in professional boxing when he knocked out 37-year-old Kelvin Price (13-0, 6 KOs) at the [[Los Angeles Memorial Sports Arena|Memorial Sports Arena]] in [[Los Angeles]], on December 15, 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-price-deal-place-khan-molina-sho-card--58701|title=Wilder-Price Deal in Place For Khan-Molina SHO Card|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> The fight was originally slated to take place in August 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-kelvin-price-set-8-4-on-fox-sports--54605|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Kelvin Price Set For 8/4 On Fox Sports|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Wilder fought patiently through the first two rounds and mostly measured Price. The fight ended when a right hand from Wilder caught Price on the jaw and sent him back into the ropes and down. He attempted to get to his feet, but struggled which led referee Ray Corona to wave an end to the bout. Wilder claimed the vacant [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] Continental Americas heavyweight title, which he went on to successfully defend twice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2012/12/deontay-wilder-destroys-kelvin-price-in-3rd-round-tko/|title=Deontay Wilder destroys Kelvin Price in 3rd round TKO!|last=|first=|date=December 15, 2012|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112182836/http://www.boxingnews24.com/2012/12/deontay-wilder-destroys-kelvin-price-in-3rd-round-tko/|archive-date=January 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/alfredo-angulo-struggles-wilder-blasts-price-three--60514|title=Alfredo Angulo Struggles, Wilder Blasts Price in Three|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n=== Rise up the ranks ===\nOn April 3, 2013, [[Golden Boy Promotions]] announced that Wilder would fight former European heavyweight champion and 2000 Olympic gold medalist [[Audley Harrison]] (31-6, 23 KOs) at the [[Sheffield Arena|Motorpoint Arena]] in [[Sheffield]], his UK debut, on April 27. Harrison was coming into this fight looking to rebuild after winning the [[Prizefighter series|prizefighter heavyweight tournament]] two months earlier. The card, which was being shown live on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] in USA, was headlined by [[Amir Khan (boxer)|Amir Khan]]'s return in the UK against [[Julio D\u00edaz (boxer)|Julio D\u00edaz]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-audley-harrison-finalized-khan-diaz--64016|title=Deontay Wilder-Audley Harrison Finalized For Khan-Diaz|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Harrison stated that he would retire if he lost.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/audley-if-wilder-beats-me-its-over-risk-worth-it--64046|title=Audley: If Wilder Beats Me It's Over, But Risk Worth It!|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Wilder knocked out Harrison in round one. Wilder found an opening 49 seconds into the opening round and caught Harrison with a big right hand that rocked him back into the ropes. A follow-up barrage from Wilder sent Harrison into the corner, crumpling onto the floor. Harrison used the ropes to get to his feet at the count of eight, but referee Terry O'Connor called off the bout. The official time of stoppage was 1:22 of the first round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2013/4/27/4275666/wilder-vs-harrison-results-deontay-wilder-scores-first-round-tko-boxing-news|title=Deontay Wilder scores first round TKO|last=|first=|date=April 27, 2013|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112182827/http://www.badlefthook.com/2013/4/27/4275666/wilder-vs-harrison-results-deontay-wilder-scores-first-round-tko-boxing-news|archive-date=January 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/apr/27/audley-harrison-crumbles-defeat-70-seconds|title=Audley Harrison crumbles to defeat to Deontay Wilder in 70 seconds|last=|first=|date=April 27, 2013|website=www.theguardian.com|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112191025/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/apr/27/audley-harrison-crumbles-defeat-70-seconds|archive-date=January 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/anthony-ogogo-wins-big-debut-wilder-kos-harrison--64896|title=Anthony Ogogo Wins Big In Debut; Wilder KO's Harrison|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Four days after the fight, Harrison announced his retirement at the age of 41 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/22324777|title=Audley Harrison hints at retirement after defeat by Deontay Wilder|last=|first=|date=April 27, 2013|website=BBC Boxing|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509183302/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/22324777|archive-date=May 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, [[Frank Warren (promoter)|Frank Warren]] announced a card that would take place at the [[Wembley Arena]] in [[London]] on June 15, 2013, which would feature Wilder and British boxer [[Dereck Chisora]] as the main event. Prior to the announcement, Golden Boy and Wilder's camp stated there was no deal in place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/frank-warren-wilder-chisora-set-6-15-wembley-arena--65339|title=Frank Warren: Wilder-Chisora Set, 6/15 At Wembley Arena|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-05|language=en-us}}</ref> The fight fell through after Wilder was arrested in May following a domestic assault in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/9423373/deontay-wilder-face-sergei-liakhovich|title=Deontay Wilder to fight on Aug. 9|last=|first=|date=June 26, 2013|website=ESPN|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729174057/http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/9423373/deontay-wilder-face-sergei-liakhovich|archive-date=July 29, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Days later, Wilder signed [[Al Haymon]] as his new advisor.<ref>[https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-brings-al-haymon-reach-next-level--65599 Wilder Brings in Al Haymon To Reach \"The Next Level\"] - Boxing Scene, 16 May 2016</ref>\n\nIn June, Golden Boy announced Wilder would main event a triple header of a Showtime card at the [[Fantasy Springs Resort Casino|Fantasy Springs Casino]] in [[Indio, California]] against former [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] heavyweight champion [[Siarhei Liakhovich]] (25-5, 16 KOs) on August 9, 2013 in a ten-round bout. Liakhovich would fight for the first time in nearly a year and half.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-liakhovich-card-coming-together-fantasy-springs--67062|title=Wilder-Liakhovich card coming together at Fantasy Springs|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Wilder knocked Liakhovich out in the first round. Wilder caught Liakhovich with a big right hand; while Liakhovich was backed against the ropes, he went down heavily and began twitching. The referee waved an end to the bout without beginning a count. Liakhovich was kept down for some time in the ring, before being helped to a stool.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10495021/deontay-wilder-demonstrated-ko-power-against-siarhei-liakhovich|title=Deontay Wilder demonstrated KO power against Siarhei Liakhovich|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116153834/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10495021/deontay-wilder-demonstrated-ko-power-against-siarhei-liakhovich|archive-date=January 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-scary-first-round-ko-liakhovich--68487|title=Deontay Wilder in Scary First Round KO of Liakhovich|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2013/8/9/4607936/shobox-results-deontay-wilder-smashes-siarhei-liakhovich-in-1-43|title=Deontay Wilder smashes Siarhei Liakhovich in 1:43|last=|first=|date=August 9, 2013|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116163819/http://www.badlefthook.com/2013/8/9/4607936/shobox-results-deontay-wilder-smashes-siarhei-liakhovich-in-1-43|archive-date=January 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Days after the fight, Liakhovich filed a protest to change the outcome as 'no contest' citing that Wilder hit him with illegal punches. Liakhovich claimed he was punched behind the ear and neck area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/liakhovich-protest-claims-wilder-illegal-punches--68677|title=Liakhovich To Protest, Claims Wilder Used Illegal Punches|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/liakhovich-moves-forward-with-protest-wilder-ko--69317|title=Liakhovich Moves Forward With Protest of Wilder KO|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nTwo months later in October, Wilder knocked out Nicolai Firtha (21-10-1, 8 KOs) in four rounds to maintain his knockout streak. Prior to the stoppage, Firtha was dropped twice in the opening round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-drills-game-firtha-fourth-round--71025|title=Deontay Wilder Drills a Game Firtha in Fourth Round|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> In February 2014 it was announced that Wilder would fight 33 year old [[Malik Scott]] (36-1-1, 13 KOs) in an eliminator for the WBC heavyweight title. The fight took place on the undercard of [[Danny Garcia (Boxer)|Garcia]]-[[Mauricio Herrera|Herrera]] at the [[Coliseo Rub\u00e9n Rodr\u00edguez|Coliseo Ruben Rodriguez]] in [[Puerto Rico]] on March 15.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2014/02/deontay-wilder-vs-malik-scott-to-be-a-wbc-heavyweight-eliminator-bout-on-315/|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Malik Scott to be a WBC heavyweight eliminator bout on 3/15|last=|first=|date=February 7, 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013053940/https://www.boxingnews24.com/2014/02/deontay-wilder-vs-malik-scott-to-be-a-wbc-heavyweight-eliminator-bout-on-315/|archive-date=October 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> When the fight was first announced, Wilder was #3 in the WBC ratings while Scott was #26. Wilder knocked out Scott at 1:36 of the first round. Wilder started off with slow jabs and the knockout blow appeared to be a straight right hand, which many believe did not connect clearly. There was an instant reaction from the crowd and on social media regarding how the fight ended. Scott was said to be unhappy about reports that he took a dive and congratulated Wilder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ringtv.com/325649-deontay-wilder-vs-malik-scott-live-round-by-round-updates/|title=Deontay Wilder 96-Second KO Malik Scott Live Round-By-Round Updates|last=|first=|date=March 15, 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116153956/http://www.ringtv.com/325649-deontay-wilder-vs-malik-scott-live-round-by-round-updates/|archive-date=January 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2014/3/15/5513506/gif-deontay-wilder-knocks-out-malik-scott-but-did-the-punches-really|title=Deontay Wilder knocks out Malik Scott, but did the punches really land?|last=|first=|date=March 15, 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024180023/http://www.badlefthook.com/2014/3/15/5513506/gif-deontay-wilder-knocks-out-malik-scott-but-did-the-punches-really|archive-date=October 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2014/03/malik-scott-unhappy-that-people-think-he-faked-ko-loss-to-wilder/|title=Malik Scott unhappy that people think he faked KO loss to Wilder|last=|first=|date=March 17, 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013053926/https://www.boxingnews24.com/2014/03/malik-scott-unhappy-that-people-think-he-faked-ko-loss-to-wilder/|archive-date=October 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> This set Wilder up as [[mandatory challenger]] for the WBC heavyweight title held by new champion [[Bermane Stiverne]], who had defeated [[Chris Arreola]] for the title vacated by the retiring [[Vitali Klitschko]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/10614575/deontay-wilder-scores-31st-ko-many-fights|title=Wilder bests Scott; 31st KO in as many fights|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2016-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150805010444/http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/10614575/deontay-wilder-scores-31st-ko-many-fights|archive-date=2015-08-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Wilder fought journeyman and former Prizefighter finalist Jason Gavern (25-16-4, 11 KOs) in a 10-round bout. The fight took place at the [[Stubhub Center (tennis)|StubHub Center]] in [[Carson, California]] on the undercard of the [[IBF]] [[welterweight]] fight between [[Shawn Porter vs. Kell Brook|Shawn Porter and Kell Brook]] fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theboxingobserver.com/2014/08/deontay-wilder-stays-busy-with-gavern-weekend-bout-american-wants-fury-in-september-then-klitschko/|title=Deontay Wilder faces Jason Gavern Saturday, American wants big Fury/Klitschko fights next year|last=|first=|date=August 15, 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226100917/http://www.theboxingobserver.com/2014/08/deontay-wilder-stays-busy-with-gavern-weekend-bout-american-wants-fury-in-september-then-klitschko/|archive-date=December 26, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gavern was knocked down in rounds three and four. His corner threw in the towel after round four giving Wilder another stoppage victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9426436/deontay-wilder-stopped-jason-gavern-in-california-to-make-it-32-0-with-32-knockouts|title=Deontay Wilder stopped Jason Gavern in California to make it 32-0 with 32 knockouts|last=|first=|date=August 17, 2014|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118030715/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9426436/deontay-wilder-stopped-jason-gavern-in-california-to-make-it-32-0-with-32-knockouts|archive-date=January 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2014/8/16/6025003/deontay-wilder-stops-jason-gavern-after-four-rounds|title=Deontay Wilder stops Jason Gavern after four rounds|last=|first=|date=August 16, 2014|website=|publisher=|access-date=January 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226021402/https://www.badlefthook.com/2014/8/16/6025003/deontay-wilder-stops-jason-gavern-after-four-rounds|archive-date=December 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===WBC heavyweight champion===\n==== Wilder vs. Stiverne ====\n[[File:Deontay Wilder 2015.jpg|thumb|Wilder in 2015]]\nOn January 17, 2015, billed as \"Return to Glory\", Wilder fought Stiverne at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in Las Vegas, Nevada for the WBC heavyweight title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/stiverne-wilder-clash-coming-together-early-2015--84405|title=Stiverne-Wilder Clash Coming Together For Early 2015|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Wilder became the first American heavyweight world champion since [[Hasim Rahman]] by defeating Stiverne by a [[unanimous decision]] after twelve rounds. The judges scored it 118\u2013109, 119\u2013108, and 120\u2013107. Stiverne landed 110 of 327 punches (34%) with Wilder landing 227 of 621 punches (37%). Wilder had some big rounds, particularly rounds two and seven, where he threw a barrage of power shots. Wilder showed that he could go twelve rounds and utilized his jab throughout.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9650590/boxing-deontay-wilder-outpoints-bermane-stiverne-to-earn-wbc-heavyweight-title|title=Boxing: Deontay Wilder outpoints Bermane Stiverne to earn WBC heavyweight title|website=Sky Sports|access-date=2016-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427205421/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9650590/boxing-deontay-wilder-outpoints-bermane-stiverne-to-earn-wbc-heavyweight-title|archive-date=2016-04-27|url-status=live}}</ref> This was the first real proof to critics that Wilder could go the distance and could box, as up to that point he had finished all opponents inside the distance. After the fight, Wilder dedicated his win to his disabled daughter, and to his boxing hero [[Muhammad Ali]], who had turned 73 years old that same day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/12187869/deontay-wilder-decisions-bermane-stiverne-become-first-american-heavyweight-champion-2006|title=Wilder ends American heavyweight drought|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018191724/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/12187869/deontay-wilder-decisions-bermane-stiverne-become-first-american-heavyweight-champion-2006|archive-date=2017-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref> The fight averaged 1.24 million viewers, peaking at 1.34 million on Showtime.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ringtv.com/377339-deontay-wilder-bermane-stiverne-draws-high-ratings-for-showtime/|title=Deontay Wilder-Bermane Stiverne draws high ratings for Showtime - The Ring|date=2015-01-21|work=The Ring|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019003435/https://www.ringtv.com/377339-deontay-wilder-bermane-stiverne-draws-high-ratings-for-showtime/|archive-date=2017-10-19|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[Nevada Athletic Commission|Nevada State Athletic Commission]] (NSAC), Wilder earned $1 million and Stiverne received $910,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/dan-rafael/post/_/id/11676/stiverne-wilder-purses-revealed|title=Stiverne-Wilder purses revealed|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019003659/http://www.espn.com/blog/dan-rafael/post/_/id/11676/stiverne-wilder-purses-revealed|archive-date=2017-10-19|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after the fight, Wilder cut his relationship with Golden Boy Promotions and Al Haymon became his new manager.<ref>[https://www.boxingscene.com/golden-boy-prez-wilder-most-talented-division-beats-joshua--124537 Golden Boy Prez: Wilder is Most Talented in Division, Beats Joshua] - Boxing Scene, 22 January 2018</ref>\n\n==== Wilder vs. Molina ====\nOn May 8, 2015, Wilder announced that he would make his first defense in his homestate of Alabama, which would be the first heavyweight title fight held in the state. Wilder last fought in Alabama in 2012. Showtime confirmed they would televise the bout live on June 13 at [[Bartow Arena]], [[Birmingham, Alabama]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-return-6-13-alabama-eyes-active-2015--90763|title=Wilder To Return 6/13 in Alabama, Eyes Active 2015|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Shortly after, WBC #14 [[\u00c9ric Molina|Eric Molina]] (23-2, 17 KOs) was announced as Wilder's opponent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-pumped-face-eric-molina-home--90936|title=Deontay Wilder Pumped To Face Eric Molina at Home|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> After receiving some backlash for choosing Molina as his first defense, Wilder claimed there were other options, but their asking prices were too high.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-explains-why-molina-selected--91762|title=Deontay Wilder Explains Why Molina Was Selected|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Molina was aiming to become the first [[Mexican Americans|Mexican-American]] world heavyweight champion in history. A sold-out crowd of 9,347 was announced. Wilder dominated, knocking down Molina near the end of round four, twice in the fifth, and knocking him out onto his back in the ninth round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-survives-early-scare-stops-molina-nine--92289|title=Wilder Survives Early Scare, Stops Molina In Nine|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-03|language=en-us}}</ref> Wilder showed respect for Molina after the bout, stating \"I was really surprised he kept coming and hanging in there. A lot of people said he wouldn't even be around, he wouldn't last. There were a lot of doubters, but he showed a lot of heart, and I needed that kind of guy to fight here in Alabama.\" Wilder was ahead on all three judges' scorecards at the time of stoppage 90\u201377, 89\u201378, and 89\u201378. According to [[CompuBox]] Punch stats, Wilder landed 141 of 303 thrown (47%) whilst Molina landed just 49 of 188 (26%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/13074424/deontay-wilder-retains-wbc-heavyweight-title-knockout-eric-molina|title=Wilder KO's Molina, retains heavyweight title|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107112329/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/13074424/deontay-wilder-retains-wbc-heavyweight-title-knockout-eric-molina|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9884408/deontay-wilder-knocked-eric-molina-out-after-nine-rounds-in-alabama|title=Deontay Wilder knocked Eric Molina out after nine rounds in Alabama|website=Sky Sports|access-date=2016-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427214801/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9884408/deontay-wilder-knocked-eric-molina-out-after-nine-rounds-in-alabama|archive-date=2016-04-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2015/6/13/8777179/wilder-vs-molina-results-deontay-wilder-retains-wbc-belt-with-9th|title=Wilder stops Molina in ninth round|date=2015-06-13|website=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102073319/http://www.badlefthook.com/2015/6/13/8777179/wilder-vs-molina-results-deontay-wilder-retains-wbc-belt-with-9th|archive-date=2017-01-02|url-status=live}}</ref> The fight aired on Showtime and averaged 678,000 viewers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2015/06/deontay-wilder-vs-eric-molina-averages-678k-viewers-on-showtime/|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Eric Molina averages 678K viewers on Showtime \u00bb Boxing News|date=2015-06-16|work=Boxing News 24|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107113314/http://www.boxingnews24.com/2015/06/deontay-wilder-vs-eric-molina-averages-678k-viewers-on-showtime/|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Wilder earned $1.4 million for the fight compared to Molina, who received a $250,000 purse.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.fightsaga.com/news/item/6694-Wilder-vs-Washington-purses|title=Wilder vs Washington purses|last=Cleveland|first=Lee|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en-gb|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606061522/http://www.fightsaga.com/news/item/6694-Wilder-vs-Washington-purses|archive-date=2017-06-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Wilder vs. Duhaupas ====\n\nIn August 2015, it was announced that Wilder would make his second defense against WBC #12 [[Johann Duhaupas]] (32-2, 20 KOs) on September 26 at the [[Birmingham\u2013Jefferson Convention Complex|Legacy Arena]], Alabama.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/duhaupas-officially-out-eu-clash-wilder-shot--94856|title=Duhaupas Officially Out of EU Clash, For Wilder Shot|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-05|language=en-us}}</ref> In front of a hometown crowd of 8,471 in attendance, Wilder beat Duhaupas by TKO in the eleventh round. Duhaupas, who was battered and bloodied, claimed he still had plenty of fight left when referee Jack Reiss waved off his brave challenge. Duhaupas had never been stopped before in his career inside the distance. It was a very one sided fight\u200a\u2060\u2014\u200a\u2060after taking punishment in round seven, referee Jack Reiss went over to Duhaupas' corner telling him he would need to do more or he would stop the fight. Wilder was ahead 100\u201390, 99\u201390, and 99\u201391 on judges' scorecards at the time of stoppage, having landed 326 of 587 punches thrown (56%) whilst Duhaupas landed 98 of 332 (30%). In the post fight, Wilder praised Duhaupas' toughness, saying \"We knew he was tough. We knew he was mentally tough. We knew he was going to come. That's why you can't criticize nobody you don't know. The most scariest people are the ones you don't know.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/13749903/deontay-wilder-stops-johann-duhaupas-11th-round-maintain-wbc-heavyweight-title|title=Wilder dominates Duhaupas, improves to 35-0|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107015609/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/13749903/deontay-wilder-stops-johann-duhaupas-11th-round-maintain-wbc-heavyweight-title|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10008278/deontay-wilder-stops-johann-duhaupas-in-11-rounds|title=Deontay Wilder stops Johann Duhaupas in 11 rounds|website=Sky Sports|access-date=2016-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412081200/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10008278/deontay-wilder-stops-johann-duhaupas-in-11-rounds|archive-date=2016-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref> For the fight, Wilder made $1.4 million and Duhaupas earned a $140,000 purse.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2015/09/wilder_duhaupas_purse_weigh-in.html|title=Weigh-in complete, purses official for Deontay Wilder's heavyweight title fight against Johann Duhaupas in Birmingham|work=AL.com|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107003541/http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2015/09/wilder_duhaupas_purse_weigh-in.html|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> The fight was the main event of [[Premier Boxing Champions]] on [[NBC Sports|NBC]] and averaged 2.2 million viewers, peaking at 3 million viewers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2015/09/wilder-duhaupas-averages-2-2-million-viewers-on-nbc/|title=Wilder-Duhaupas averages 2.2 million viewers on NBC \u00bb Boxing News|date=2015-09-30|work=Boxing News 24|access-date=2017-05-29|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107015201/http://www.boxingnews24.com/2015/09/wilder-duhaupas-averages-2-2-million-viewers-on-nbc/|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Wilder vs. Szpilka ====\n\nIn December 2015, Showtime confirmed that terms had been agreed for Wilder to defend his WBC title against Polish boxer [[Artur Szpilka]] (20-1, 15 KOs) on January 16, 2016, at the [[Barclays Center]], [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], where the winner would be scheduled to fight WBC mandatory challenger [[Alexander Povetkin]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-szpilka-confirmed-jan-16-barclays-center--99125|title=Wilder-Szpilka Confirmed, Jan. 16 At Barclays Center|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-05|language=en-us}}</ref> A crowd of 12,668 mostly pro-Polish fans was announced. Szpilka looked very strong as the bout began, and won the first three rounds with his awkward southpaw stance, rapid foot movement, and talent for slipping punches. Szpilka made Wilder appear wild with his punches, as Wilder missed 175 punches thrown at Szpilka, mostly head punches. Entering round nine, Szpilka, aware from the ring commentators he could no longer win the fight on the cards, changed strategy and took a gamble. Going to the inside, Szpilka swung for the rafters, but Wilder read Szpilka and connected first with a powerful right hand to the face. Szpilka fell to the canvas, and his head jerked backwards in a reflex motion, abruptly ending the competitive contest and sending the ringside physicians and emergency medical personnel immediately into the ring. Wilder reportedly earned a career-high $1.5 million compared to Szpilka who had a $250,000 purse.<ref name=\":0\" /> The fight averaged 500,000 viewers and peaked at 623,000 viewers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-szpilka-tv-ratings-not-indicative-overall-exposure--100632|title=Wilder-Szpilka TV Ratings Not Indicative Of Overall Exposure|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-05|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nAfter the fight, newly crowned heavyweight champion [[Tyson Fury]] entered the ring going face-to-face in a heated verbal exchange with Wilder, calling him out. In the post fight press conference, Wilder rated his performance at 5/10. Wilder was not in a celebratory mood and said his concerns for Szpilka meant he was not in the mood for the confrontation with Fury. Wilder explained \"We risk our lives in there for your entertainment. I want to knock my opponents out, but not hurt them. I want them to be able to go home to their family.\" Szpilka regained consciousness before leaving the ring on a stretcher, and recovered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/14586613/deontay-wilder-ko-artur-szpilka-9th-round|title=Wilder rocks Szpilka with KO, then jaws with Fury|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2016-04-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408025536/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/14586613/deontay-wilder-ko-artur-szpilka-9th-round|archive-date=2016-04-08|url-status=live}}</ref> The knockout was voted \"Knockout of The Year\" by [[Premier Boxing Champions]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-vs-szpilka-pbc-knockout-year--112162|title=Wilder vs. Szpilka - PBC's Knockout of The Year|last=|first=|date=December 28, 2016|website=Boxing Scene|publisher=|access-date=December 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Wilder vs. Povetkin cancelled fight====\nWilder was due to make the fourth defense of his WBC heavyweight title against former [[WBA (Regular)]] champion and mandatory challenger Alexander Povetkin (30-1, 22 KOs) on May 21, 2016 at the [[Megasport Arena]] in [[Moscow]], Russia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-signed-contract-povetkin-defense--103507|title=Deontay Wilder Has Signed Contract For Povetkin Defense|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-05|language=en-us}}</ref> Povetkin was considered by many to be Wilder's toughest opponent to date, and was on a four-fight knockout streak since suffering his only defeat to [[Wladimir Klitschko]] in late 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2016/3/29/11323446/promoter-announces-deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-will-be-held-at|title=Wilder-Povetkin scheduled for 5/21 in Moscow|date=29 March 2016|publisher=|access-date=25 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425224603/http://www.badlefthook.com/2016/3/29/11323446/promoter-announces-deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-will-be-held-at|archive-date=25 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Wilder did not seem to be worried by the defense and saw this as a big name in the heavyweight division that he could add to his legacy, saying \"Going to Russia is going to be nothing for me, I'm going to treat it like it's the U.S. because at the end of the day, it's one man, one ring. When I knock him out and come back, it's going to bring my legacy even bigger than it is now.\" He also added, \"I think this is going to be an easier fight than Stiverne, I really believe that. To be proven wrong, we're going to find out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2016/04/deontay_wilder_undaunted_by_ru.html/|title=Wilder believes easy fight against Povetkin|publisher=|access-date=2016-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425224442/http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2016/04/deontay_wilder_undaunted_by_ru.html|archive-date=2016-04-25|url-status=dead}}</ref> World of Boxing promoter Andrey Ryabinsky won the rights for the fight with a winning purse bid of $7.15 million, higher than the $5,1 million bid from [[Lou DiBella]]. Due to the 70-30 split, Wilder was looking at a minimum $4,504,500, a career-high payday.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/14851951/andrey-ryabinsky-wins-purse-bid-deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-fight|title=Ryabinsky wins purse bid for Wilder-Povetkin|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-10-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026163458/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/14851951/andrey-ryabinsky-wins-purse-bid-deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-fight|archive-date=2017-10-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHowever, a week before the fight on May 14, it was reported that Povetkin had tested positive for the banned substance [[meldonium]]. Promoter Andrei Ryabinsky added that Povetkin did take meldonium in 2015, but stopped before it was banned, and only \"leftover traces of meldonium at a very low concentration (70 nanograms)\" were found in a blood sample given by the 36-year-old last month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/sport/20160514/1039595026/meldonium-povetkin-doping.html/Povetkin's|title=Doping Sample Contains 7%|publisher=}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10281387/alexander-povetkin-fails-drugs-test-ahead-of-deontay-wilder-fight|title=Povetkin failed drug test|last=|first=|date=|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=May 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517172141/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10281387/alexander-povetkin-fails-drugs-test-ahead-of-deontay-wilder-fight|archive-date=May 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Hours after, Wilder and his team skipped their flight to Moscow; the WBC, having little choice what with the titleholder preparing to return home, postponed the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/15551134/wbc-postpones-deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-fight-failed-drug-test|title=Wilder-Povetkin called off after failed drug test|access-date=2016-07-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806124611/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/15551134/wbc-postpones-deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-fight-failed-drug-test|archive-date=2016-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/15551134/wbc-postpones-deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-fight-failed-drug-test| title = WBC postpones Deontay Wilder Alexander Povetkin fight| access-date = 2016-05-15| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160521132050/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/15551134/wbc-postpones-deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-fight-failed-drug-test| archive-date = 2016-05-21| url-status=live}}</ref> Jay Deas, Wilder's manager and trainer, said the fight is off as did promoter Lou DiBella. Andrey Ryabinskiy, promoter for Povetkin, claimed the fight would take place at a later date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boxingjunkie.usatoday.com/2016/05/15/deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-title-bout-postponed-meldonium/|title=Deontay Wilder-Alexander Povetkin title bout postponed following Russian's positive meldonium test|date=2016-05-15|website=Boxingjunkie|access-date=2016-07-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721052631/http://boxingjunkie.usatoday.com/2016/05/15/deontay-wilder-alexander-povetkin-title-bout-postponed-meldonium/|archive-date=2016-07-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Wilder claimed he is still interested in fighting and beating Povetkin in the future, as this was a fight he had trained hard for and was hoping to make a statement against an elite heavyweight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10285420/deontay-wilder-still-wants-to-give-alexander-povetkin-a-whipping|title=Wilder still wants Povetkin fight|last=|first=|date=|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520114314/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10285420/deontay-wilder-still-wants-to-give-alexander-povetkin-a-whipping|archive-date=2016-05-20|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 14, 2017, Wilder won $7 million plus legal fees after taxes, in court, over the cancellation of the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/other-sports/89398063/us-boxer-deontay-wilder-wins-7m-doping-suit-in-a-unanimous-jury-decision|title=US boxer Deontay Wilder wins $7m doping suit in a unanimous jury decision|website=Stuff|access-date=2017-02-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406171325/http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/other-sports/89398063/us-boxer-deontay-wilder-wins-7m-doping-suit-in-a-unanimous-jury-decision|archive-date=2017-04-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/dibella-we-won-wilder-lawsuit-against-povetkin-promoter--113576|title=DiBella: We Won Wilder's Lawsuit Against Povetkin, Promoter - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-14}}</ref>\n\n==== Wilder vs. Arreola ====\nFollowing Wilder's return to the USA, on May 26, former two-time world title challenger Chris Arreola (36-4-1-2, 31 KOs) became the front runner to challenge Wilder. At the time, Arreola was not ranked by the WBC because he had tested positive for [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] after his fight against [[Travis Kauffman]]. His 90-day suspension ended in March 2016 and was likely to re-enter the WBC rankings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-chris-arreola-play-summer-showdown--105034|title=Deontay Wilder-Chris Arreola in Play For Summer Showdown|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-14|language=en-us}}</ref> By June 13, the fight was confirmed and would take place on July 16, 2016 at the [[Legacy Arena]], Birmingham, Alabama.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/chris-arreolas-trainer-confirms-deontay-wilder-fight-716--105651|title=Chris Arreola's Trainer Confirms Deontay Wilder Fight For 7/16|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-14|language=en-us}}</ref> For the fight, Wilder wore white trunks with black trim, featuring a portrait of his personal idol and the late heavyweight boxing legend Muhammad Ali who had died recently. The attendance at the arena was announced 11,974. Wilder dominated the entire fight with his sharp jab, which caused severe swelling to Arreola's left eye. In the fourth round, Wilder connected with a heavy right cross that knocked Arreola down. After eight rounds, Arreola's cornermen informed the referee to stop the contest. After the fight, Wilder stated he had broken his right hand and torn his biceps during the fight. Wilder was ahead 80\u201371, 80\u201371, and 79\u201372 on the scorecards at the time of stoppage. According to CompuBox statistics, Wilder landed 152 of 346 punches (44 percent), and Arreola landed 52 of 188 (28 percent).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/17091750/deontay-wilder-defeats-chris-arreola-eighth-round-tko-retains-heavyweight-title|title=Wilder routs Arreola despite significant injuries|last=|first=|date=|website=ESPN|publisher=|access-date=2016-07-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721025257/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/17091750/deontay-wilder-defeats-chris-arreola-eighth-round-tko-retains-heavyweight-title|archive-date=2016-07-21|url-status=live}}</ref> For the fight, Wilder earned $1.4 million to $150,000 which was received by Arreola.<ref name=\":0\" /> The fight averaged 1.8 million viewers on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] and peaked at 2.54 million viewers, with the whole telecast averaging 1.45 million viewers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2016/07/wilder-vs-arreola-averaged-1-8m-viewers-fox/|title=Wilder vs. Arreola averaged 1.8M viewers on Fox \u00bb Boxing News|date=2016-07-20|work=Boxing News 24|access-date=2018-03-09|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310074002/http://www.boxingnews24.com/2016/07/wilder-vs-arreola-averaged-1-8m-viewers-fox/|archive-date=2018-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-arreola-145-million-viewers-last-among-major-networks--106891|title=Wilder-Arreola, 1.45 Million Viewers: Last Among Major Networks|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-03-09|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAccording to promoter Lou DiBella, Wilder spent most of the night at [[UAB Hospital]]. He would be back at the hospital soon, likely for two surgeries, one to repair each injury. This ruled him out for the remainder of 2016. \"Deontay is definitely out for the remainder of the year, but we will know more in the next few days,\" DiBella said.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/17097709/deontay-wilder-rest-16-suffering-2-big-injuries-ko-win-chris-arreola|title=Wilder's fight injuries rule him out for rest of '16|access-date=2016-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160720021106/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/17097709/deontay-wilder-rest-16-suffering-2-big-injuries-ko-win-chris-arreola|archive-date=2016-07-20|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== Wilder vs. Washington ====\nWilder announced in November that he had fully recovered and was back in training following surgery. His return fight was scheduled to be in early 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-back-full-training-injuries-fully-healed--110810|title=Deontay Wilder Back in Full Training, Injuries Are Fully Healed|last=|first=|date=November 17, 2016|website=Boxing Scene|publisher=|access-date=December 21, 2016}}</ref> In December, Peter Fury announced there were active talks to get [[Hughie Fury]] a world title fight against Wilder for the first quarter of 2017. Fury would not be considered as a voluntary due to being ranked at number 26 by the WBC, but Peter hoped Fury would be bumped into the top 15 after the WBC convention in December.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2016/12/06/news/exclusive-peter-fury-aims-to-finalize-deontay-wilder-v-hughie|title=Peter Fury aims to finalize Deontay Wilder v Hughie|last=|first=|date=December 6, 2016|website=www.worldboxingnews.net|publisher=|access-date=December 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222001429/http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2016/12/06/news/exclusive-peter-fury-aims-to-finalize-deontay-wilder-v-hughie|archive-date=December 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn December 21, 2016, according to Wilder's manager Jay Deas, there were advance talks for a fight to take place on February 25, 2017, at the [[Birmingham\u2013Jefferson Convention Complex|Legacy Arena]] in Alabama against 29-year-old two-time [[Poland|Polish]] heavyweight champion and former world title challenger [[Andrzej Wawrzyk]] (33-1, 19 KOs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ringtv.com/478158-wilder-advanced-talks-face-wawrzyk-feb-25-fox/|title=WILDER IN ADVANCED TALKS TO FACE WAWRZYK ON FEB. 25 ON FOX|last=|first=|date=December 20, 2016|website=RingTV|publisher=|access-date=December 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222000717/http://www.ringtv.com/478158-wilder-advanced-talks-face-wawrzyk-feb-25-fox/|archive-date=December 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-andrzej-wawrzyk-february-25--111964|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Andrzej Wawrzyk on Tap For February 25|last=|first=|date=December 20, 2016|website=Boxing Scene|publisher=|access-date=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Wawrzyk was on a six-fight knockout streak, with a win in his most recent fight over veteran [[Albert Sosnowski]], since his only loss to Alexander Povetkin, inside the distance in May 2013. Terms were agreed to a day later as the date and venue were confirmed on December 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2016/12/22/news/deontay-wilder-v-andrzej-wawrzyk-a-go-for-february-25-in-alabama|title=Deontay Wilder v Andrzej Wawrzyk 'a go' for February 25 in Alabama|last=|first=|date=December 22, 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=December 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222225410/http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2016/12/22/news/deontay-wilder-v-andrzej-wawrzyk-a-go-for-february-25-in-alabama|archive-date=December 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/18363743/heavyweight-world-titleholder-deontay-wilder-defend-andrzej-wawrzyk-feb-25|title=Deontay Wilder to defend heavyweight world title against Andrzej Wawrzyk|last=|first=|date=December 29, 2016|website=[[ESPN]]|publisher=|access-date=December 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229184936/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/18363743/heavyweight-world-titleholder-deontay-wilder-defend-andrzej-wawrzyk-feb-25|archive-date=December 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After announcing Wawrzyk as his opponent, Wilder received criticism from fellow boxers, boxing experts and fans for choosing \"an easy fight\", having yet another voluntary defense and not fighting a top-level heavyweight. On December 29, Wilder spoke about the criticism, not believing Wawrzyk should be written off, stating, \"I don't believe 'You're going to suck because I don't know you', that's just the ignorance of your average boxing fan ... I wish fans would stop criticizing fighters because it takes a lot to get in the ring.\" Wilder used [[Manny Pacquiao]] as an example for when he was little known.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2683142-deontay-wilder-vs-andrzej-wawrzyk-fight-date-announced-comments-reaction|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Andrzej Wawrzyk: Fight Date Announced, Comments, Reaction|last=|first=|date=December 21, 2016|website=|publisher=|access-date=December 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230002141/http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2683142-deontay-wilder-vs-andrzej-wawrzyk-fight-date-announced-comments-reaction|archive-date=December 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-hits-back-critics-his-opponent-wawrzyk--112178|title=Deontay Wilder Hits Back at Critics of His Opponent Wawrzyk|last=|first=|date=December 29, 2016|website=Boxing Scene|publisher=|access-date=December 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn January 25, 2017, it was reported that Wawrzyk had failed a drug test, ruling him out of the fight. With a month to go until the fight, Wilder was determined that he would find a replacement to fight him on short notice and not postpone the fight card.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-hunts-new-opponent-wawrzyk-fails-ped-test--112959|title=Deontay Wilder Hunts For New Opponent, Wawrzyk Fails PED Test - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/18548198/heavyweight-andrzej-wawrzyk-tests-positive-anabolic-steroid-stanozolol|title=Heavyweight Wawrzyk tests positive for steroids|newspaper=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127101042/http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/18548198/heavyweight-andrzej-wawrzyk-tests-positive-anabolic-steroid-stanozolol|archive-date=2017-01-27|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Luis Ortiz (Cuban boxer)|Luis Ortiz]] put himself forward for the fight only to be shot down due to him failing drug tests in the past.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/luis-ortiz-deontay-wilder-im-ready-fight-you-on-february-25--112992|title=Luis Ortiz To Deontay Wilder: I'm Ready To Fight You on Feb. 25! - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-01-27}}</ref> [[Tyson Fury]] also put himself forward.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2017/01/tyson-fury-volunteers-fight-deontay-wilder/|title=Tyson Fury volunteers to fight Deontay Wilder - Boxing News|date=2017-01-26|newspaper=Boxing News 24|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127111632/http://www.boxingnews24.com/2017/01/tyson-fury-volunteers-fight-deontay-wilder/|archive-date=2017-01-27|url-status=live}}</ref> A day later it was reported that 35-year-old [[Gerald Washington (boxer)|Gerald Washington]] (18-0-1, 12 KOs) was in the lead of landing the world title fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ringtv.com/482256-washington-play-search-wilder-opponent-three/|title=Washington in play as search for Wilder's opponent down to three - The Ring|date=2017-01-26|newspaper=The Ring|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127112133/http://www.ringtv.com/482256-washington-play-search-wilder-opponent-three/|archive-date=2017-01-27|url-status=live}}</ref> It was announced on January 30, 2017, that Washington would face Wilder on February 25.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/boxing/la-sp-sn-boxing-gerald-washington-deontay-wilder-fox-20170130-story.html|title=Former USC football player Gerald Washington gets heavyweight title shot at Deontay Wilder|last=Pugmire|first=Lance|website=latimes.com|access-date=2017-01-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170130232841/http://www.latimes.com/sports/boxing/la-sp-sn-boxing-gerald-washington-deontay-wilder-fox-20170130-story.html|archive-date=2017-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn front of a hometown crowd of 12,346, Wilder won by TKO in round five. Washington started off strong with power punches as Wilder moved around with jabs. Midway through the fifth, Wilder got Washington against the ropes and landed a combination of power shots, the last shot being a left to the head of Washington, dropping him backwards against the ropes. Washington recovered quickly on unsteady legs. The fight resumed, and Wilder unloaded heavy blows to Washington's head, eventually leading referee Michael Griffin to halt the fight at 1 minute and 45 seconds of the round.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/deontay-wilder-gerald-washington-result-video-wbc-title-bout/y40p1yn2ekqk1954h443syruo|title=Deontay Wilder beats Gerald Washington with fifth-round TKO|date=2017-02-26|work=Sporting News|access-date=2017-02-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227062422/http://www.sportingnews.com/other-sports/news/deontay-wilder-gerald-washington-result-video-wbc-title-bout/y40p1yn2ekqk1954h443syruo|archive-date=2017-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> Wilder credited his patience in the post-fight interview, \"I knew he was going to come in excited to fight for a world title. I just kept calm and found my rhythm. I knew he was going to tire out, and when he did, I took advantage. It was all about timing. I'm very smart in the ring when it comes to using different tactics.\" At the time of stoppage, one judge had the fight 39\u201337 for Wilder, whilst the remaining two judges had the fight 38\u201338 after four rounds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ringtv.com/486324-deontay-wilder-kos-gerald-washington-round-5/|title=Deontay Wilder KOs Gerald Washington in Round 5 - The Ring|date=2017-02-25|work=The Ring|access-date=2017-02-27|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227094359/http://www.ringtv.com/486324-deontay-wilder-kos-gerald-washington-round-5/|archive-date=2017-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-starts-slow-stops-gerald-washington-five-results--113991|title=Deontay Wilder Starts Slow, Stops Gerald Washington in Five - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref> Washington earned $250,000 from the fight while Wilder earned $900,000. CompuBox Stats showed that Wilder landed 33 of 113 punches thrown (29%) and Washington connected with 30 of his 98 thrown (31%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/18768383/deontay-wilder-knocks-gerald-washington-fifth-round-retain-heavyweight-world-title|title=Wilder finishes Washington in 5th, retains title|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304172002/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/18768383/deontay-wilder-knocks-gerald-washington-fifth-round-retain-heavyweight-world-title|archive-date=2017-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref> The fight was televised on Fox in the US and was watched by an average audience of 1.76 million viewers, peaking at 1.86 million. The bout was the most watched boxing match in the United States for 2017, until the [[Keith Thurman|Thurman]]-[[Danny Garcia (Boxer)|Garcia]] unification fight drew 3.74 million on March 4.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-washington-peaked-186-million-viewers-averaged-176m--114079|title=Wilder-Washington Peaked at 1.86 Million Viewers; Averaged 1.76M - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/thurman-garcia-fight-peaked-51m-viewers-averaged-374m--114381|title=Thurman-Garcia Fight Peaked at 5.1M Viewers; Averaged 3.74M - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-03-11}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the fight, there was an altercation between Wilder and [[Dominic Breazeale]], who had knocked out [[Izu Ugonoh|Izuagbe Ugonoh]] on the undercard. Breazeale claimed that Wilder and his entourage attacked him in front of his wife at the [[Westin Hotels & Resorts|Westin]] Birmingham hotel. This came after Breazeale supposedly had a fracas with Wilder's younger brother, Marsellos, at ringside during Wilder's fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/breazeale-i-attacked-by-wilder-mob-front-wife-kids--114008|title=Breazeale: I Was Attacked by Wilder, Mob in Front of Wife, Kids - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/video-deontay-wilder-dominic-breazeale-scuffle-hotel-lobby--114015|title=Video: Deontay Wilder, Dominic Breazeale Scuffle in Hotel Lobby - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==== Wilder vs. Stiverne II ====\nOn February 27, 2017, the WBC ordered Wilder to fight mandatory challenger Bermane Stiverne, with negotiations to begin immediately.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/wbc-orders-stiverne-vs-wilder-ii-395763|title=WBC orders Stiverne vs. Wilder II \u2022 Boxing News|date=2017-02-27|work=Boxing News|access-date=2017-02-27|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227232218/http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/wbc-orders-stiverne-vs-wilder-ii-395763|archive-date=2017-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2017/02/27/news/wilder-v-stiverne-ii-ordered-negotiation-period-begins-today|title=Wilder v Stiverne II ordered, negotiation period begins today|last=Stiverne|first=Wilder v|website=WBN - World Boxing News|access-date=2017-02-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227115212/http://www.worldboxingnews.net/2017/02/27/news/wilder-v-stiverne-ii-ordered-negotiation-period-begins-today|archive-date=2017-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 18, 2017, it was reported that a deal was being negotiated for Wilder to make his sixth defense of his WBC title against heavyweight contender Luis Ortiz (27-0, 23 KOs, 2 NC). Wilder's promoter Lou DiBella, had put the Barclays Center in Brooklyn on hold for October 14 and November 4, 2017. According to sources, [[Don King (boxing promoter)|Don King]], promoter of Bermane Stiverne, mandatory challenger for Wilder, had reported to be working out a step-a-side fee from Wilder and Ortiz's advisor Al Haymon. Stiverne told Boxing Scene that Don King had not been given any permission to negotiate a step-a-side fee and he would work with his management team to ensure he challenges for the WBC title in his next fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/stiverne-hires-prince-dubin-not-allow-wilder-ortiz--118643|title=Stiverne Hires Prince and Dubin - Will NOT Allow Wilder-Ortiz - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref> It was reported by VADA, who oversees the WBC Clean Boxing Programme, that Stiverne missed a drug test. The WBC treated this as failing a drug test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-manager-concerned-stiverne-missed-his-drug-test--118772|title=Wilder's Manager Concerned That Stiverne Missed His Drug Test - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-07-23}}</ref> WBC president Mauricio Sulaiman&nbsp;worked on a deal to finalise Wilder vs. Ortiz for November 4, 2017. According to TheRing.tv, Stiverne agreed a mid six-figure payday&nbsp;to allow the fight to take place.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ringtv.com/504960-deontay-wilder-luis-ortiz-talks-heavyweight-title-clash/|title=Roadblock cleared: Deontay Wilder, Luis Ortiz slated to meet on Nov. 4 - The Ring|date=2017-08-31|work=The Ring|access-date=2017-09-07|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170907214718/https://www.ringtv.com/504960-deontay-wilder-luis-ortiz-talks-heavyweight-title-clash/|archive-date=2017-09-07|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 12, it was reported by Showtime that the fight was a done deal, awaiting official announcement for the fight to take place on November 4 at Barclays Center in Brooklyn. Showtime revealed the card would include [[Daniel Jacobs (boxer)|Daniel Jacobs]] as chief support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-ortiz-jacobs-lipinets-showtime-tripleheader-play--120421|title=Wilder-Ortiz, Jacobs, Lipinets Showtime Tripleheader in Play - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-09-13}}</ref> On September 18, the fight was made official pending the official press conference, which would take place the next day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11042633/deontay-wilders-defence-against-luis-ortiz-confirmed-for-november-4|title=Deontay Wilder's defence against Luis Ortiz confirmed for November 4|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2017-09-19|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122035042/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11042633/deontay-wilders-defence-against-luis-ortiz-confirmed-for-november-4|archive-date=2017-11-22|url-status=live}}</ref> [[ESPN]] was advised that Stiverne would fight Breazeale on the undercard in a title eliminator.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/20747217/deontay-wilder-fight-king-kong-luis-ortiz-november|title=Wilder to take on Ortiz in 1st fight since Feb.|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-09-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920052706/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/20747217/deontay-wilder-fight-king-kong-luis-ortiz-november|archive-date=2017-09-20|url-status=live}}</ref> It was reported on September 29, Ortiz had failed a drugs test. It was believed that the drugs in question were [[diuretic]]s [[Chlorothiazide|chlorothaizide]] and [[hydrochlorothiazide]], which are used to treat [[Hypertension|high blood pressure]] but also can be used as masking agents for [[Performance-enhancing substance|performance-enhancing drug]]&nbsp;use. A urine sample was taken on September 22 in Miami. Ortiz never informed VADA that he had been on medication.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/20856410/luis-ortiz-fails-drug-test-bout-deontay-wilder-canceled|title=Ortiz fails drug test; Wilder bout to be canceled|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314042444/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/20856410/luis-ortiz-fails-drug-test-bout-deontay-wilder-canceled|archive-date=2018-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 4, the WBC withdrew its sanction on the Wilder vs. Ortiz fight and ordered Wilder to fight mandatory Stiverne (25-2-1, 21 KOs).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-vs-stiverne-rematch-ordered-by-wbc-luis-ortiz-out--121095|title=Wilder vs. Stiverne Rematch Ordered By WBC, Luis Ortiz is Out! - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-06}}</ref> The next day, Showtime announced the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-vs-stiverne-rematch-announced-by-showtime--121122|title=Wilder vs. Stiverne Rematch Announced By Showtime - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-06}}</ref> At the press conference, Wilder claimed that he was happy to be getting Stiverne out of the way.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ringsidereport.com/?p=69211|title=Deontay Wilder \u2013 Bermane Stiverne Press Conference ERUPTS|date=2017-10-05|work=Ringside Report|access-date=2017-10-06|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007003506/http://ringsidereport.com/?p=69211|archive-date=2017-10-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Stiverne officially signed the contract on October 17, his managers Josh Dubin and James Prince confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/bermane-stiverne-signs-contract-deontay-wilder-rematch--121531|title=Bermane Stiverne Signs Contract For Deontay Wilder Rematch - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref> Stiverne weighed 254\u00be pounds on the scales, 13 pounds more than he weighed in the first fight and 34 pounds more than Wilder, who came in at 220\u00be pounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/stiverne-weighs-254-pounds-wilder-weights--122084|title=Stiverne Weighs 254\u00be Pounds, 15 More Than 1st Fight With Wilder - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-11-04}}</ref> It was revealed that Wilder would earn a purse of $1.4 million and Stiverne would take home $506,250 as mandatory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2017/11/purses-wilder-1-4m-stiverne-506k/|title=Purses: Wilder $1.4M, Stiverne $506K \u00bb Boxing News|date=2017-11-04|work=Boxing News 24|access-date=2017-11-04|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105212255/http://www.boxingnews24.com/2017/11/purses-wilder-1-4m-stiverne-506k/|archive-date=2017-11-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn fight night, in front of 10,924, Wilder retained his WBC title with a commanding first-round knockout. Wilder knocked Stiverne down three times before referee Arthur Mercante stopped the fight at 2:59 of the round. Wilder started the fight using his jab to keep Stiverne at distance. A right hand put Stiverne down for the first knockdown. As soon as the fight resumed, Wilder landed another right hand, putting Stiverne down a second time. The final knockdown saw Stiverne against the ropes, when Wilder connected with another right, followed by a left hook to the head. At this point, with Stiverne defenseless, the fight was stopped. In the post fight interview, Wilder said, \"You have to give props to Stiverne for getting in the ring. It takes a lot of courage and it takes a lot of pride to step in the ring with someone like me. We do what we have to do in the ring and at least he stepped up. He was a clean fighter.\" When asked about a future fight with [[Anthony Joshua]], he said, \"I've been waiting on that fight for a long time now. I declare war upon you. Do you accept my challenge? I've been waiting for a long time. I know I'm the champion. I know I'm the best. Are you up for the test?\" With the win, Wilder had now knocked out every opponent he had fought.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-destroys-bermane-stiverne-one-round-results--122136|title=Deontay Wilder Destroys Bermane Stiverne in One Round - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11114357/wilder-vs-stiverne-ii-deontay-wilder-crushes-bermane-stiverne-in-the-opening-round-in-brooklyn|title=Wilder vs Stiverne II: Deontay Wilder crushes Bermane Stiverne in the opening round in Brooklyn|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2017-11-05|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105051631/http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11114357/wilder-vs-stiverne-ii-deontay-wilder-crushes-bermane-stiverne-in-the-opening-round-in-brooklyn|archive-date=2017-11-05|url-status=live}}</ref> CompuBox Stats showed that Stiverne threw only 2 jabs and 2 power shots, not landing any. Wilder landed 15 of his 39 punches thrown (38%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/21292423/deontay-wilder-defeats-bermane-stiverne-first-round-knockout|title=Wilder delivers on promise, KOs Stiverne in 1st|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-11-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105050154/http://www.espn.com/boxing/story/_/id/21292423/deontay-wilder-defeats-bermane-stiverne-first-round-knockout|archive-date=2017-11-05|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/compubox-stiverne-lands-zero-punches-wilder-rematch--122149|title=CompuBox: Stiverne Lands \"Zero\" Punches in Wilder Rematch! - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref> The fight drew an average of 824,000 viewers and peaked at 887,000 viewers on Showtime. This was slightly less than the first fight, which took place in January 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-stiverne-rematch-peaked-887000-viewers-on-showtime--122212|title=Wilder-Stiverne Rematch Peaked at 887,000 Viewers on Showtime - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-11-08}}</ref>\n\n==== Wilder vs. Ortiz ====\n{{Main|Deontay Wilder vs. Luis Ortiz}}\nLuis Ortiz made his return to the ring after the failed drugs test by knocking out journeyman Daniel Martz on December 8. Wilder was sat ringside on commentary for the fight. After the fight, Ortiz called out Wilder, who then stepped into the ring and said to Ortiz, \"I guarantee you, you'll have the fight.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/photos-luis-ortiz-trades-words-with-deontay-wilder-win--123235|title=Photos: Luis Ortiz Trades Words With Deontay Wilder After Win|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-09|language=en-us}}</ref> On December 19, negotiations resumed between Wilder and Ortiz, with a potential fight for Wilder's WBC heavyweight title to take place at the Barclays Center in Brooklyn on March 3, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-luis-ortiz-works-march-3-barclays-center--123590|title=Deontay Wilder-Luis Ortiz in Works for March 3 at Barclays Center|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-20|language=en-us}}</ref> According to RingTV on December 30, an agreement had been reached.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ringtv.com/525581-deontay-wilder-luis-ortiz-agree-heavyweight-title-fight-march-3-new-york/|title=Deontay Wilder, Luis Ortiz agree to heavyweight title fight on March 3 in New York - The Ring|date=2017-12-30|work=The Ring|access-date=2018-01-01|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180102072858/https://www.ringtv.com/525581-deontay-wilder-luis-ortiz-agree-heavyweight-title-fight-march-3-new-york/|archive-date=2018-01-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Terms were agreed on January 12 and the fight was officially announced on January 23.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/22062270/heavyweight-titleholder-deontay-wilder-giving-luis-king-kong-ortiz-another-chance|title=Wilder giving Ortiz another chance|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114020324/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/22062270/heavyweight-titleholder-deontay-wilder-giving-luis-king-kong-ortiz-another-chance|archive-date=2018-01-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-luis-ortiz-official-march-3-barclays--124233|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Luis Ortiz - Official For March 3, Barclays|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-13|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-ortiz-charlo-centeno-double-made-official-march-3--124569|title=Wilder-Ortiz, Charlo-Centeno Double Made Official - March 3|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-01-24|language=en-us}}</ref> Wilder weighed his lowest since turning professional in 2006, at 214 pounds. Ortiz came in at 241\u00bc pounds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-weighs-only-214-pounds-ortiz-comes-241--125819|title=Wilder Weighs in at Only 214 Pounds; Ortiz Comes in at 241\u00bc|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-03-03|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nWilder overcame difficulty and knocked Ortiz out in round ten to retain his WBC title in front of a crowd of 14,069. Both boxers started the fight cautious with Wilder throwing the jab, however Ortiz seemed to do more in the opening four rounds throwing combinations. Wilder took control in round five, knocking Ortiz down once. Wilder was hurt badly in round seven by a left hand from Ortiz. Wilder was then trapped on the ropes taking head and body shots from Ortiz. Referee David Fields kept a close eye on the Wilder and appeared to be close to stopping the fight, but Wilder survived the round. Despite Ortiz not managing to drop Wilder in round seven, all three judges scored the round 10\u20138 for Ortiz. Wilder used rounds eight and nine to rest up and managed to avoid any punishment. Wilder hurt Ortiz with a right hand at the end of round nine. Wilder then unloaded on Ortiz, who at this point looked tired, in round ten in dropping him twice before the match was halted by David Fields. The official time of the stoppage was at 2:05 of round ten.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-knocks-ortiz-out-tenth-results--125874|title=Deontay Wilder Survives Huge Scare, Knocks Ortiz Out in Tenth|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-03-09|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nAt the time of stoppage, all three judges had their scorecards 85\u201384 in favor of Wilder.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-luis-ortiz-official-scorecards-photo--125877|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Luis Ortiz - Official Scorecards - Photo|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-03-09|language=en-us}}</ref> After the fight, Wilder spoke about his win and praised Ortiz, \"'King Kong' ain't got nothing on me. A true champion always finds a way to come back, and that's what I did tonight. Luis Ortiz is definitely a crafty guy. He put up a great fight. We knew we had to wear him down. I showed everyone I can take a punch. When Ortiz leaves tonight, he can hold his head high. He gave the fans a hell of a fight.\" Ortiz also gave his thoughts on the fight. Speaking through a translator, he said, \"I feel fine. I did receive a right hand, but I'm OK. I was listening to the directions that my corner was giving me. In this sport, any punch can end a fight. It was a great fight and I performed well.\" According to CompuBox Stats, Wilder landed 98 of 346 punches thrown (28%) and Ortiz landed 87 of his 363 thrown (24%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-luis-ortiz-compubox-punch-stats--125891|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Luis Ortiz - CompuBox Punch Stats|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-03-09|language=en-us}}</ref> For the fight, Wilder earned a career-high $2.1 million and Ortiz received a $500,000 purse. The event was Barclays Center's second-biggest boxing crowd after [[Keith Thurman|Thurman]] vs. [[Danny Garc\u00eda|Garc\u00eda]], which was attended by 16,533 in March 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/22639658/heavyweight-champion-deontay-wilder-knocks-luis-ortiz-10th-round-defend-title|title=Wilder brutally KO's Ortiz, 'ready' to unify title|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2018-03-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309001053/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/22639658/heavyweight-champion-deontay-wilder-knocks-luis-ortiz-10th-round-defend-title|archive-date=2018-03-09|url-status=live}}</ref> The fight averaged 1.1 million viewers and peaked at 1.2 million on Showtime. The last time Showtime did over 1 million viewers was in 2015 when Wilder defeated Stiverne for the WBC title.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-ortiz-showtime-highest-rated-fight-wilder-stiverne--125952|title=Wilder-Ortiz Showtime's Highest-Rated Fight Since Wilder-Stiverne|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-03-09|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==== Wilder vs. Fury ====\n{{Main|Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury}}\nFrom April until the end of June 2018, both camps of Joshua and Wilder were in talks around a heavyweight unification fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/joshuas-promoter-plans-make-new-offer-wilder--127694|title=Joshua's Promoter Plans To Make a \"New\" Offer To Wilder|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref> The main hurdles were purse split, date and venue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/hearn-cautions-joshua-wilder-2-3-weeks-get-done--127744|title=Hearn Cautions That Joshua-Wilder Has 2\u20133 Weeks To Get Done|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/joshua-wilder-hearn-reveals-postitive-talks-70-chance-deal--127770|title=Joshua-Wilder: Hearn Reveals Postitive &#91;sic&#93; Talks, 70% Chance of Deal|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/hearn-joshua-wants-wilder-he-wants-fight-uk--128039|title=Hearn: Joshua Wants Wilder \u2013 But He Wants The Fight in The UK|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-joshua-wanted-one-way-rematch-clause-pick-officials--129558|title=Wilder: Joshua Wanted One-Way Rematch Clause, to Pick Officials|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref> At one point Wilder had agreed to fight Joshua in the UK, however there were confusions in the contracts that were being sent back and forth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-ive-agreed-joshua-fight-uk-ball-their-court--129019|title=Wilder: I've Agreed To Joshua Fight In UK, Ball In Their Court!|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref> At the same time, [[Eddie Hearn]] was working a deal out for Joshua to fight WBA mandatory challenger Alexander Povetkin (34-1, 24 KOs).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/alexander-povetkin-expects-fight-anthony-joshua-fall--128709|title=Alexander Povetkin Expects To Fight Anthony Joshua in The Fall|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/joshua-vs-povetkin-deal-close-being-finalized-says-hearn--128903|title=Joshua vs. Povetkin Deal Close To Being Finalized, Says Hearn|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref> Negotiations took a turn on June 26 when the WBA gave Joshua's camp 24 hours to finalize a deal with Povetkin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wba-gives-joshua-24-hours-close-deal-povetkin-fight--129452|title=WBA Gives Joshua 24 Hours to Close Deal for Povetkin Fight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref> With Joshua closer to fighting Povetkin in September 2018, Hearn stated the Joshua-Wilder fight would still take place in April 2019 at Wembley Stadium.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/joshua-wilder-happen-on-april-13-wembley-says-hearn--129491|title=Joshua-Wilder Can Happen On April 13 At Wembley, Says Hearn|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref> Hearn later explained that the WBA would have granted an exemption, had Wilder signed a deal to fight Joshua.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/hearn-joshua-needed-wilder-sign-get-exemption-from-wba--129501|title=Hearn: Joshua Needed Wilder to Sign to Get Exemption From WBA|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-us}}</ref> On July 16, Joshua vs. Povetkin was announced for September 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11438629/joshua-vs-povetkin-anthony-joshua-defends-world-titles-against-alexander-povetkin-at-wembley|title=Joshua vs Povetkin: Anthony Joshua defends world titles against Alexander Povetkin at Wembley|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922175145/https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11438629/joshua-vs-povetkin-anthony-joshua-defends-world-titles-against-alexander-povetkin-at-wembley|archive-date=2018-09-22|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 30, it was reported that there were ongoing negotiations for a fight to take place in either November or December 2018 between former unified heavyweight world champion Tyson Fury (27-0, 19 KOs) and Wilder.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/fury-confirms-negotiations-with-wilder-december-fight--130442|title=Fury Confirms Negotiations With Wilder For December Fight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-08-31|language=en-us}}</ref> On July 31, Fury stated the fight against Wilder was 99% a done deal, with only a location and date to be confirmed. Fury also had to come through in his bout against [[Francesco Pianeta]] on August 18.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/tyson-fury-far-im-concerned-wilder-fight-99-done--130484|title=Tyson Fury: As Far as I'm Concerned \u2013 Wilder Fight is 99% Done!|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-08-31|language=en-us}}</ref> Wilder was scheduled to be in Belfast to further promote the fight.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-set-belfast-ringside-berth--130848|title=Deontay Wilder Set For Belfast Ringside Berth|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-08-31|language=en-us}}</ref> Fury won the bout via a points decision. During the post-fight interviews, promoter Warren confirmed the Fury vs. Wilder fight was on. The fight would take place in either Las Vegas or New York in November 2018. The fight would be aired on PPV in the United States on Showtime and in the UK on [[BT Sport Box Office|BT Sports Box Office]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.bt.com/boxing/tyson-fury-v-deontay-wilder-mega-fight-to-be-shown-exclusively-live-on-bt-sport-S11364289577993|title=Fury v Wilder mega-fight to be shown exclusively live on BT Sport|work=BT.com|access-date=2018-08-31|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831211719/http://sport.bt.com/boxing/tyson-fury-v-deontay-wilder-mega-fight-to-be-shown-exclusively-live-on-bt-sport-S11364289577993|archive-date=2018-08-31|url-status=live}}</ref> Talking about how the fight came together, Fury said, \"We have two men who will fight anyone. This man has been trying to make a fight with another chump. They called, I answered. I said: 'Send me the contract.' They sent it. I said 'yes'.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/45236702|title=Tyson Fury and Deontay Wilder face off in ring after Briton beats Francesco Pianeta|date=2018-08-18|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-08-31|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821103718/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/45236702|archive-date=2018-08-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Warren later told BBC Radio 5 live, \"[It's a] 50\u201350 [purse split], quick and smooth negotiations. He was the world heavyweight champion. He's undefeated. [Wilder and his team] understand that. All of the terms are agreed.\" By the end of August, contracts for the fight to take place had been signed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-tyson-fury-50-50-deal-says-frank-warren--131059|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury is a 50\u201350 Deal, Says Frank Warren|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-08-31|language=en-us}}</ref> On September 22, both fighters confirmed they had signed the contract and the fight would take place on December 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.bt.com/boxing/tyson-fury-and-deontay-wilder-agree-december-1-date-for-fight-S11364297208878|title=Tyson Fury and Deontay Wilder agree December 1 date for fight|work=BT.com|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922173746/http://sport.bt.com/boxing/tyson-fury-and-deontay-wilder-agree-december-1-date-for-fight-S11364297208878|archive-date=2018-09-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/45611289|title=Deontay Wilder v Tyson Fury: Fight confirmed for 1 December|date=2018-09-22|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-09-22|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922064516/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/45611289|archive-date=2018-09-22|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the [[California State Athletic Commission]], Wilder would earn a guaranteed base purse of $4 million and Fury would take home a guaranteed purse of $3 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/now?nowId=21-41046609-4|title=Per the California State Athletic Commission, purses for Saturday's Wilder-Fury card: Deontay Wilder $4 million, Tyson Fury $3 million (both stand to earn millions more from their percentage of the profits from the event); Jarrett Hurd $1 million, Jason Welborn $30,000; Luis Ortiz $375,000, Travis Kauffman $125,000; Joe Joyce $40,000, Joe Hanks $50,000; Carlos Licona $30,000, Mark Anthony Barriga $25,000; Julian Williams $30,000, Francisco Javier Castro $2,500; Jessie Rodriguez $7,000, Josue Morales $6,000; Chris Arreola $25,000, Maurenzo Smith $16,000; Robert Guerrero $25,000, Adam Mate $2,500; Isaac Lowe $5,000, Lucas Rafael Baez $2,500. Anthony Yarde and Alfredo Angulo are off the show because opponents could not be secured.|date=2018-12-01|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305122242/http://www.espn.com/espn/now?nowId=21-41046609-4|archive-date=2019-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite Frank Warren's original claim that the revenue would be split 50-50, it was revealed that Wilder could make $14 million (\u00a310.94 million) and Fury would earn around $10.25 million (\u00a38 million). Both boxers would see this increase to their base purses after receiving their percentages from pay-per-view revenue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/boxing/1051813/Fury-vs-Wilder-Prize-Money-Deontay-Wilder-and-Deontay-Wilder-Purses-Revealed|title=Fury vs Wilder prize money: Deontay Wilder and Tyson Fury's purses revealed|last=Malata|first=Chisanga|date=2018-11-29|work=Express.co.uk|access-date=2018-11-29|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181130071525/https://www.express.co.uk/sport/boxing/1051813/Fury-vs-Wilder-Prize-Money-Deontay-Wilder-and-Deontay-Wilder-Purses-Revealed|archive-date=2018-11-30|url-status=live}}</ref> The weigh-in took place on November 30, on a made platform outside the [[Los Angeles Convention Center]]. Fury stepped on the scale first and weighed in at 256\u00bd pounds, his lightest since his comeback following his lay off. The weight was only 2 pounds less than he weighed in August 2018 against Francisco Pianeta, however, he looked more slim and lean. Wilder was next to step on and came in at 212\u00bd pounds, his lowest since his debut in 2008 when he weighed 207\u00bc pounds. For his last bout, Wilder weighed 214 pounds, however, it was cited that Wilder suffered from an illness during his training camp.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-weighs-even-lower-ortiz-fight-fury-256-5-weights--134196|title=Wilder Weighs In Even Lower Than For Ortiz Fight; Fury 256.5|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-12-01|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn front of a crowd of 17,698 at the Staples Center, Wilder and Fury fought a twelve-round split decision draw, meaning Wilder retained his WBC title. Mexican judge Alejandro Rochin scored the fight 115\u2013111 for Wilder, Canadian judge Robert Tapper had it 114\u2013112 for Fury and British judge Phil Edwards scored it a 113\u2013113 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-tyson-fury-official-scorecards-photo--134242|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury \u2013 Official Scorecards \u2013 Photo|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> The crowd booed at the decision with many believing Fury did enough to dethrone Wilder. Fury, using his unorthodox stance, spent much of the fight using upper and lower-body movement to avoid Wilder's big shots and stay out of range. There was not much action in round one as both boxers used the round to feel each other out. Wilder tried to trap Fury into the corner, but Fury made Wilder miss most of his big swings. In round four, Wilder bloodied Fury's nose with his stiff jabs, but was unable to follow up on the attacks. In round six, Fury switched to southpaw stance and had success backing Wilder against the ropes and at the same time stayed cautious of Wilder's power. In round seven, after trading jabs, which saw Fury come out on top, Fury landed a counter right hand, then quickly tied Wilder up before he could throw anything back. Round eight saw back and forth action with both trying to land. Wilder threw a lot of power shots which Fury mostly evaded. In round nine, Wilder dropped Fury with a short left hook followed by an overhand right. Fury beat referee Jack Reiss' count and survived the round. Having expended a lot of energy trying to finish Fury in round nine, Wilder looked fatigued in round ten. This came to as an advantage for Fury as he landed two right hands. Fury also took advantage in round eleven, landing enough shots and avoided anything Wilder could throw. In round twelve, Wilder landed a right-left combination which put Fury down hard on his back. The crowd, commentary team and Wilder believed the fight was over. Reiss looked at Fury on the canvas and began giving him a count. To everyone's surprise, Fury beat the count. Reiss made Fury walk towards him and called for the action to continue. Wilder, fatigued again, was unable to land another power shot and Fury landed some right hands to finish the round and the fight on his feet. Both boxers embraced in a hug after the final bell sounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-controversial-draw-results--134241|title=Deontay Wilder, Tyson Fury Ends in Controversial Draw|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/boxing/46416721|title=Wilder v Fury: Stunning draw in WBC world heavyweight title fight|last=|first=|date=|website=BBC Boxing|access-date=2008-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/11569434/tyson-fury-forced-to-settle-for-a-draw-with-deontay-wilder|title=Tyson Fury forced to settle for a draw with Deontay Wilder|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref>\n\nAccording to CompuBox statistics, Wilder landed 71 punches of 430 thrown (17%), and Fury landed 84 of his 327 thrown (26%). Wilder was much less accurate in this fight than he usually had been in previous fights. Fury out-landed Wilder in nine out of the twelve rounds. Both Wilder and Fury only landed double digits in four separate rounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/deontay-wilder-vs-tyson-fury-compubox-punch-stats--134262|title=Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury \u2013 CompuBox Punch Stats|last=|first=|date=|website=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> After the fight, both men gave in-ring interviews. Wilder stated, \"I think with the two knockdowns, I definitely won the fight. We poured our hearts out tonight. We're both warriors. I rushed my punches. I didn't sit still. I was too hesitant. I started overthrowing the right hand, and I just couldn't adjust. I was rushing my punches. That's something I usually don't do.\" Fury said, \"We're on away soil. I got knocked down twice, but I still believe I won that fight. I'm being a total professional here. God bless America. The 'Gypsy King' has returned. That man is a fearsome puncher, and I was able to avoid that. The world knows I won the fight. I hope I did you all proud after nearly three years out of the ring. I showed good heart to get up. I came here tonight, and I fought my heart out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/25429168|title=Wilder-Fury ends in a draw; both calls for rematch|date=2018-12-02|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> Wilder and Fury both claimed to be the best heavyweights in the world and both called out unified world champion [[Anthony Joshua]]. Fury shouted, \"Chicken! Chicken! Joshua, where are you?\" Wilder then agreed to state the two best heavyweights got into the ring and fought.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-fury-agree-were-best-division-joshua-chicken--134253|title=Wilder, Fury Agree: We're Best in Division, Joshua is a Chicken|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref>\n\nThe event was both a critical and a commercial success. The fight reportedly sold approximately 350,000 [[pay-per-view]] buys on Showtime in the United States, grossing around $30 million, making it the most lucrative heavyweight fight in the country since [[John Ruiz vs. Roy Jones Jr.]] in 2003.<ref name=\"espn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/25519401/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-fight-generates-325000-pay-per-view-buys|title=Sources: Wilder-Fury generates 325K PPV buys|date=December 12, 2018|work=[[ESPN]]|access-date=December 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181216210856/http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/25519401/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-fight-generates-325000-pay-per-view-buys|archive-date=December 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/wilder-fury-fight-max-out-325000-ppv-buys--134375|title=Wilder-Fury Fight Should Max Out At 325,000 PPV Buys|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.worldboxingnews.net/2018/12/05/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-ppv-success/|title=Deontay Wilder v Tyson Fury hailed a heavyweight Pay-Per-View success|date=December 5, 2018|work=World Boxing News|access-date=December 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205193419/https://www.worldboxingnews.net/2018/12/05/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-ppv-success/|archive-date=December 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Showtime's delayed broadcast a week later drew an average 488,000 viewers and peaked at 590,000 viewers.<ref name=\"espn\" />\n\n==== Wilder vs. Breazeale ====\nOn the evening of May 18, 2019, Wilder defended his WBC heavyweight title against Dominic Breazeale via knockout in the first round. Wilder caught him with a powerful right which sent Breazeale flat on his back and unable to continue with the referee waving off the contest after reaching the ten count.\n\n==== Wilder vs. Ortiz II ====\n{{Main|Deontay Wilder vs. Luis Ortiz II}}\n\nIn a rematch of their 2018 fight, Wilder faced Ortiz again on November 23, 2019, winning by seventh-round knockout to retain his WBC heavyweight title after being behind on all three of the judges' scorecards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/live/2019/nov/23/deontay-wilder-v-luis-ortiz-ii-live-fight|title=Deontay Wilder v Luis Ortiz II: WBC heavyweight championship \u2013 as it happened|last=Graham|first=Bryan Armen|date=2019-11-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHis rematch with Ortiz had been the sixth time Wilder had fought a boxer who was ranked in the global heavyweight top ten by [[BoxRec]] within a year of the bout. The others were [[Malik Scott]] (KO 1), Bermane Stiverne (UD 15), Luis Ortiz in their first match (TKO 10), Tyson Fury (SD 15), and Dominic Breazeale (KO 1).<Ref>[https://boxrec.com/media/index.php/BoxRec%27s_Annual_Ratings:_Heavyweight_Annuals BoxRec's Annual Ratings: Heavyweight Annuals.]</ref> \n\n==== Wilder vs. Fury II ====\n{{Main|Deontay Wilder vs. Tyson Fury II}}\n\nOn November 27, 2019, it was announced that Wilder would face Tyson Fury on February 22, 2020, in a rematch of their 2018 bout which resulted in a draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2019/11/27/20986522/deontay-wilder-tyson-fury-championship-rematch-set-feb-22-las-vegas-boxing|title=Deontay Wilder vs Tyson Fury championship rematch set for Feb. 22 in Las Vegas |author=Adam Guillen Jr.|publisher=mmamania.com|date=November 27, 2019}}</ref> Wilder lost the fight via seventh-round TKO, losing the WBC heavyweight title in the process. According to CompuBox, Fury landed 82 of his 267 total punches (31%), including 58 out of 160 power punches (36%). Wilder landed 34 of his 141 total punches (24%), including 18 out of 55 power punches (33%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxingscene.com/%20/tyson-fury-deontay-wilder-rematch-compubox-punch-stats--147018|title=Tyson Fury-Deontay Wilder Rematch - CompuBox Punch Stats|website=BoxingScene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilder has 8 children.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1EscOr1H4S8?t=176</ref> Wilder's first child, a daughter with ex-girlfriend Helen Duncan, was born in 2005 with [[spina bifida]]. Wilder also has two other daughters and one son with Jessica Scales-Wilder, whom he married in 2009 and later divorced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/news/377837-tuscaloosa-to-hold-parade-for-deontay-wilder|title=Tuscaloosa to hold parade for Deontay Wilder|author=Lem Satterfield|date=23 January 2015|work=Ring TV|access-date=8 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128231648/http://ringtv.craveonline.com/news/377837-tuscaloosa-to-hold-parade-for-deontay-wilder|archive-date=28 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Wilder is currently engaged to and has a child with Telli Swift <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fabwags.com/deontay-wilders-girlfriend-telli-swift/|access-date=2018-11-27|language=en|work=FabWags.com|title=Wilder, Telli & Kaorii|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181202155037/http://fabwags.com/deontay-wilders-girlfriend-telli-swift/|archive-date=2018-12-02|url-status=live}}</ref> and has been featured on the reality television show, [[WAGS Atlanta]].<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4-jXRvE3oDg</ref> \n\nWilder graduated from [[Central High School (Tuscaloosa, Alabama)|Tuscaloosa Central High School]] in 2004 and dreamed of playing football ([[wide receiver]]) or basketball ([[Forward (basketball)|forward]]) for his hometown [[Alabama Crimson Tide]], but the birth of his oldest daughter and poor grades caused him to attend nearby [[Shelton State Community College]] and to focus on a boxing career.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/25624990/ns/today-today_in_beijing/t/baby-daughter-inspires-olympic-boxing-hopeful/ |title=Baby daughter inspires Olympic boxer - TODAY in Beijing - TODAY.com |publisher=Today.msnbc.msn.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002062710/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/25624990/ns/today-today_in_beijing/t/baby-daughter-inspires-olympic-boxing-hopeful/ |archive-date=2012-10-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Wilder later revealed that during this time, he struggled with [[Mood disorder|depression]] and had briefly contemplated [[suicide]] via gunshot.<ref>https://sports.yahoo.com/deontay-wilder-stands-on-doorstep-of-boxing-immortality-after-staving-off-suicide-as-a-teenager-161620135.html</ref> When reflecting on the incident, he stated \"You don't think about what effect it would cause for your family, your daughter, your kids and so forth and so on... In that state of mind, you just become selfish. You think of the inner pain and the outer pain that you're feeling right at that very moment in time.\"\n \nDeontay's younger brother Marsellos Wilder is also a professional boxer. Marsellos currently fights in the [[cruiserweight (boxing)|cruiserweight]] division and has a 5\u20132 record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/en/proboxer/835616|title=BoxRec: Marsellos Wilder|website=boxrec.com|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=1\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=41\n|ko-losses=1\n|dec-wins=1\n|dec-losses=\n|dq-wins=\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|44\n|{{No2}}Loss\n|42\u20131\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Tyson Fur