]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Yoshi]]\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[List of Yoshi video games|Yoshi]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Young Link]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Princess Zelda|Zelda]]{{efn|name=Zelda}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Zero Suit Samus]]{{efn|name=Samus}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| {{Ya}}\n| ''[[Metroid]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n! style=\"text-align: left\" | Total\n| '''12'''\n| '''26'''\n| '''39'''\n| '''51''' ('''+7''' [[Downloadable content|DLC]])\n| '''76''' ('''+6''' [[Downloadable content|DLC]])\n| '''Franchise'''\n|}\n<!-- PER WP:CRYSTAL, DO NOT ADD ANY CHARACTERS WHO HAVE NOT BEEN OFFICIALLY ANNOUNCED, INCLUDING \"LEAKED\" FIGHTERS, UNLESS ADDRESSED BY A VERIFIABLE SOURCE (E.G. IGN, GAMESPOT, ETC.); PER ARCHIVED TALK PAGE DISCUSSION, DO NOT ADD ULTIMATE FIGHTER NUMBERS TO THE TABLE -->\n\n'''Notes'''\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== Non-playable characters ==\nIn addition to the roster of playable fighters, several [[Non-player character|non-playable characters]] appear as summonable items via \"Assist Trophies\" or [[Pok\u00e9 Balls]], background stage hazards, enemies, or bosses in the single-player modes. While some were specifically created for use in the ''[[Super Smash Bros]].'' series, most come from established game franchises like the playable characters.\n\n=== Summonable ===\nCertain [[Item (gaming)|items]] in the ''Super Smash Bros.'' series can be used to temporarily summon other characters into battle. The first of these, the [[Gameplay of Pok\u00e9mon#Pok\u00e9 Ball|Pok\u00e9 Ball]], was introduced in the original ''Super Smash Bros.'' game. It can be thrown to temporarily call forth a random [[List of Pok\u00e9mon|Pok\u00e9mon]], which will perform one of its signature abilities to attack opponents or affect the battle in other ways. Each ''Super Smash Bros.'' game has had a different set of Pok\u00e9mon that can appear from Pok\u00e9 Balls, though some such as [[Snorlax]] and [[Goldeen]] have appeared in multiple entries.\n\nAnother item, the Assist Trophy, was added in ''Super Smash Bros. Brawl'' and functions similarly to the Pok\u00e9 Ball. Players who pick up an Assist Trophy will summon a random character from one of Nintendo's various franchises, causing them to interfere with opponents. Available characters vary between games, and range from supporting members of already represented franchises, such as ''Super Mario''{{'s}} [[Waluigi]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Park |first1=Gene |title=Waluigi was robbed and humiliated by Nintendo, and his fans are furious |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2018/06/12/waluigi-was-robbed-and-humiliated-by-nintendo-and-his-fans-are-furious/?noredirect=on |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref> and ''Star Fox''{{'s}} Andross, to more obscure characters like the [[Sheriff (video game)|Sheriff]], [[Dr. Kawashima]] from ''[[Brain Age]]'', Saki Amamiya from ''[[Sin and Punishment]]'' and Takamaru from ''[[The Mysterious Murasame Castle]]''. Some Assist Trophies, including [[Little Mac]], [[Dark Samus]] and [[Isabelle (Animal Crossing)|Isabelle]], have gone on to appear as playable fighters in later installments. There have also been Assist Trophies based on third-party characters, such as [[Bomberman]], [[Akira Yuki]], and [[Shovel Knight]].\n\n=== Bosses ===\nThroughout the ''Super Smash Bros.'' series, most single-player modes have included several non-playable [[boss (video games)|boss]] characters. Some of these bosses were created specifically for the ''Super Smash Bros.'' franchise.\n\nMaster Hand is a glove-like being that appears in all games to date, serving as the final [[boss (video games)|boss]] of Classic Mode<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/various/various28.html|title=Master Hand|accessdate=April 21, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705090035/http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/various/various28.html|archivedate=July 5, 2013}}</ref> and, in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Melee]]'', the 50th Event Match \"Final Destination Match\". In ''Melee'', Master Hand is playable via a system glitch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supersmashbros.ign.com/articles/news/3400/Play-as-Master-Hand-Glitch-Melee|title=Play as Master Hand Glitch (Melee)|publisher=IGN Entertainment|author=puffteam|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091021192942/http://supersmashbros.ign.com/articles/news/3400/Play-as-Master-Hand-Glitch-Melee|archivedate=October 21, 2009}}</ref> He is also playable in ''Ultimate''{{'s}} Adventure Mode if certain requirements are met. ''Super Smash Bros. Melee'' introduced a left-hand counterpart to Master Hand named Crazy Hand, which appears alongside him under certain conditions. ''Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U'' introduced a new form, Master Core, a shapeshifting mass of black particles that emerge from Master Hand and Crazy Hand after their defeat.\n\n''Super Smash Bros. Melee'' introduced Giga Bowser, a larger and more monstrous version of [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]] that could be fought in the 51st Event Match, \"The Showdown\", and as a secret final opponent in the game\u2019s Adventure Mode under certain conditions. Giga Bowser uses the same abilities as Bowser, but is much stronger and has additional effects on his attacks, such as explosions and elemental damage. Giga Bowser later became Bowser's Final Smash in all subsequent games beginning with ''Super Smash Bros. Brawl'', with players able to control him for the duration of the Final Smash.\n\nTabuu is the villain of ''Super Smash Bros. Brawl''{{'s}} story mode, ''The Subspace Emissary''. He is a humanoid [[apparitional experience|apparition]] composed of pure energy, with a single eye-shaped object located where a person's stomach would be. He can conjure several weapons for use in battle, including a rapier and large chakram; change his size at will, and teleport. Towards the end of ''The Subspace Emissary'', it is revealed that Tabuu is the entity that controlled Master Hand and the true [[antagonist]] behind the events of the story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea17.html|title=Mysteries of the Subspace Emissary|work=Smash Bros. DOJO!!|publisher=Smashbros.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130805035749/http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea17.html|archivedate=August 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''The Subspace Emissary'' also features other boss characters,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea04.html|title=Petey Piranha|work=Smash Bros. DOJO!!|publisher=Smashbros.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019080703/http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea04.html|archivedate=October 19, 2013}}</ref> like [[Petey Piranha]], [[Ridley (Metroid)|Ridley]], [[Ridley (Metroid)|Meta Ridley]], [[List of EarthBound characters#Characters|Porky]], and [[Rayquaza]]. Ridley eventually became playable in ''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'', with Meta Ridley as an alternate costume for him, while Petey Piranha became DLC character Piranha Plant's Final Smash. Three original bosses are also featured: Tabuu, the giant cyborg Galleom, and the twin-bodied robot Duon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea15.html|title=Boss Strategies|work=Smash Bros. DOJO!!|publisher=Smashbros.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019080011/http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea15.html|archivedate=October 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' introduces Galeem, a seraphic menace who serves as the main villain of ''World of Light''. Known as the \"lord of light\" and \"the ultimate enemy\", Galeem destroys the ''Smash Bros.'' world, robs all the fighters except Kirby of their physical forms, and plans on creating a new world to the point of creating an army of puppet fighters powered by enslaved spirits. Galeem is opposed by Dharkon, a one-eyed creature with many tentacles. Described as the \"embodiment of chaos and darkness\", Dharkon seeks to defeat Galeem and consume the world in darkness. Galeem and Dharkon are aided by a swarm of Master Hand and Crazy Hand puppets respectively. The mode also features bosses Giga Bowser, Galleom, [[Ganon]], [[List of Kirby characters#Marx|Marx]], [[Monster Hunter|Rathalos,]] and [[Dracula (Castlevania)|Dracula]], who also appear as final opponents for different characters in the game's Classic Mode.\n\nOther boss characters from represented franchises may appear as hazards on certain stages and attack the fighters in the middle of a battle, such as the Yellow Devil from ''[[Mega Man]]'' and Metal Face from ''[[Xenoblade Chronicles (video game)|Xenoblade Chronicles]]''.\n\n=== Other ===\nIn each of the games, there is a group of generic enemy characters based on other fighters fought in large groups in the games' single-player campaigns and \"Multi-Man Smash\" minigames. In the Japanese versions of the games, these characters are called the {{nihongo|\"Mysterious Small Fry Enemy Corps\"|\u8b0e\u306e\u30b6\u30b3\u6575\u8ecd\u56e3}}. In the English localized versions of the games, they are given names that describe their physical form. These include the Fighting Polygon Team in the original game, the Fighting Wire Frames in ''Melee'', the Fighting Alloy Team in ''Brawl''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/various/various21.html|title=STADIUM: Multi-Man Brawl|work=Smash Bros. DOJO!!|publisher=Smashbros.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019080502/http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/various/various21.html|archivedate=October 19, 2013}}</ref> and the Fighting Mii Team in ''for Nintendo 3DS/Wii U'' and ''Ultimate''. Along with ''Melee''{{'s}} Adventure Mode came the inclusion of minor, generic enemies, such as [[Goomba]]s from the ''Super Mario'' series and [[Octorok]]s from ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/wikis/super-smash-bros-melee/Adventure|title=Adventure - Super Smash Bros. Melee Wiki Guide - IGN|website=IGN}}</ref> This trend continues into ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'', which also includes an assortment of original characters to serve as non-playable generic enemies led by the Subspace Army. Many generic enemies from various games appear as part of the \"Smash Run\" mode in ''Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS''.\n\nThe Subspace Army are the antagonists of ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'', appearing in ''The Subspace Emissary'' and led by the Ancient Minister. Their goal is to pull the entire world into Subspace piece by piece using devices called Subspace Bombs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea03.html|title=The Subspace Army|work=Smash Bros. DOJO!!|publisher=Smashbros.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116065352/http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea03.html|archivedate=January 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"subspaceenemies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea06.html|title=The Enemies From Subspace|work=Smash Bros. DOJO!!|publisher=Smashbros.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019081357/http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/gamemode/modea/modea06.html|archivedate=October 19, 2013}}</ref> The Sandbag appears in every game's \"Home-Run Contest\" minigame beginning with ''Super Smash Bros. Melee''. The object is to do as much damage as possible to Sandbag in ten seconds, then strike it with either a [[Baseball bat|Home-Run Bat]] or a fighting move to launch it as far as possible.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smashbros.com/en_US/howtoplay/mode.html#homerun-contest|title=More Features: Home-Run Contest|accessdate=September 4, 2019|work=Super Smash Bros. Ultimate}}</ref> Sandbag also appears randomly as an item that drops other items when hit in various other modes in all games from ''Brawl'' onward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/item15.html|title=STADIUM: Home Run Contest|accessdate=April 19, 2008|work=Smash Bros. DOJO!!|publisher=Smashbros.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019080506/http://www.smashbros.com/wii/en_us/items/item15.html|archivedate=October 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEach installment has an [[announcer|in-game announcer]] who calls out the fighters' names before and after matches, as well as other gameplay elements. The announcer's voice is also used in many of the promotional materials for the games. The role has been taken on by [[Jeff Manning]] in the original game, Dean Harrington in ''Melee'', [[Pat Cashman]] in ''Brawl'', and [[Xander Mobus]] in ''for Nintendo 3DS/Wii U'' and ''Ultimate''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/XanderMobusVO/status/1006652458104307714|title=So I guess there was a gaming conference or something with some cool stuff announced? Either way...I'M BACK, BABY!|last=Mobus|first=Xander|date=2018-06-12|website=@xandermobusvo|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> The announcer's voice actor traditionally voices Master Hand and Crazy Hand as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gamerant.com/smash-bros-wii-u-narrator-voice/|work=Game Rant|title=\u2018Super Smash Bros.\u2019 Announcer Records Funny Voice Clips For NeoGAF Forums|last=Gates|first=Christopher|date=November 10, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104021845/https://gamerant.com/smash-bros-wii-u-narrator-voice/|archivedate=November 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gameranx.com/updates/id/25112/article/super-smash-bros-4-announcer-recorded-custom-lines-for-web-forum-neogaf/|work=[[Gameranx]]|title=Super Smash Bros. 4 Announcer Recorded Custom Lines for Web Forum NeoGAF|last=Ponce|first=Tony|date=November 10, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104005732/http://gameranx.com/updates/id/25112/article/super-smash-bros-4-announcer-recorded-custom-lines-for-web-forum-neogaf/|archivedate=November 4, 2016}}</ref> Other characters appear in non-interactive forms that do not affect gameplay, such as collectible trophies depicting their likeness or as spectators watching a battle on specific stages.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n*{{Officialwebsite|https://www.smashbros.com/en_US/fighter/index.html|''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' fighter list}}\n\n{{Super Smash Bros.}}\n\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros.| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of Nintendo characters|Super Smash Bros.]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros. lists]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros. fighters| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Characters in the ''Super Smash Bros.'' series}}\n[[File:Smash Bros Ultimate banner.png|alt=|thumb|upright=2.6|A mural featuring the fighters in ''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' as of January 16th 2020, which included every playable character in the series up until then]]\nThe [[fighting game]] series ''[[Super Smash Bros.]]'' from [[Nintendo]], launched in 1999, features an assortment of video game characters from different franchises. There are over 80 playable characters across the series, mostly sourced from Nintendo franchises but with a number of third-party ones as well. There are also other [[non-player character]]s that take the form of enemies, [[Boss (video gaming)|bosses]], and [[power-up]]s.\n\n== Playable characters ==\nEach game in the series has a number of playable characters, referred to as \"fighters\", that are taken primarily from Nintendo franchises. There are 82 total fighters across the series, with six additional downloadable content characters for ''Super Smash Bros. Ultimate'' still to be revealed.<ref name=SSBUDLC>{{cite web |last1=Patches |first1=Matt |title=Super Smash Bros. DLC will add 5 characters to the roster |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/11/1/18051896/super-smash-bros-ultimate-dlc-characters-price-release-date |website=Polygon}}</ref> Starting with ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]'', characters from non-Nintendo franchises began to make playable appearances. At the start of each game, some of the fighters will be locked from play. To unlock a hidden fighter, players need to clear certain conditions and defeat that fighter in a match. In [[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U|''Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS'' and ''Wii U'']] and ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]'', players can make their own [[Mii]] Fighters that can be customized with three different fighting styles and costume pieces unlocked through gameplay or purchased as downloadable content. Several of these costumes are based on characters and franchises not otherwise represented, such as Geno from ''[[Super Mario RPG]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Minor |first1=Jordan |title=\u2018Undertale\u2019s\u2019 Sans Is Basically a Brand New \u2018Smash Bros.\u2019 Fighter |url=https://www.geek.com/games/undertales-sans-is-basically-a-brand-new-smash-bros-fighter-1803088/ |website=Geek.com |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> [[Heihachi Mishima]] from ''[[Tekken]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farokhmanesh |first1=Megan |title=Super Smash Bros. adds Roy and Ryu to the roster today |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3-2015/2015/6/14/8778053/super-smash-bros-roy-update-e3-2015 |website=Polygon |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> and [[Sans (Undertale)|Sans]] from ''[[Undertale]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.destructoid.com/sans-from-undertale-is-getting-a-costume-in-smash-ultimate-565839.phtml | title = Sans from Undertale is getting a costume in Smash Ultimate | first = Peter | last =Glogowski  |date = September 4, 2019 | accessdate = September 4, 2019 | work = [[Destructoid]] }}</ref> All games have featured fighters that largely share their moves and abilities with another fighter on the roster, but with minor differences in their presentation and gameplay. In ''Ultimate'', several of these characters were officially labeled as \"Echo Fighters\". They have an option to either be displayed next to or within the character portrait from which they are based on.\n\n<!-- PER WP:CRYSTAL, DO NOT ADD ANY CHARACTERS WHO HAVE NOT BEEN OFFICIALLY ANNOUNCED, INCLUDING \"LEAKED\" FIGHTERS, UNLESS ADDRESSED BY A VERIFIABLE SOURCE (E.G. IGN, GAMESPOT, ETC.); PER ARCHIVED TALK PAGE DISCUSSION, DO NOT ADD ULTIMATE FIGHTER NUMBERS TO THE TABLE -->\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Fighter<!--Do not add the fighter numbers from Ultimate.-->\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 5em;\"| [[Super Smash Bros. (video game)|64]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 5em;\"| ''[[Super Smash Bros. Melee|Melee]]''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 5em;\"| ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl|Brawl]]''\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 5em;\"| [[Super Smash Bros. for Nintendo 3DS and Wii U|for ''3DS'' and ''Wii U'']]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 5em;\"| ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate|Ultimate]]''\n! scope=\"col\" | [[List of video game franchises|Franchise]] <!-- Use series indicated in the games; do not speculate -->\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Banjo & Kazooie]]<!--Do not change to \"Banjo-Kazooie\"; they are referred to as \"Banjo & Kazooie\" in-game.-->\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| data-sort-value=\"Y (DLC)\" {{Yes2|{{Abbr|DLC|Downloadable content}}}}\n| ''[[Banjo-Kazooie (series)|Banjo-Kazooie]]''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Bayonetta (character)|Bayonetta]]\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| {{Na}}\n| data-sort-value=\"Y (DLC)\" {{Yes2|{{Abbr|DLC|Downloadable conten